INSERT IGNORE INTO document_versions(id, document_id, version_number, title, content, status, created_by_id, created_at) VALUES
(1, 1, 1, 'First draft of Q1 financial report', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report - First Draft</h1><p>This preliminary report outlines the financial performance for the first quarter of fiscal year 2026. Revenue projections indicate a 15% increase compared to Q4 2025, driven primarily by strong performance in the enterprise software division. Initial calculations show total revenue of approximately $4.2M, though these figures require validation from the accounting department. Operating expenses have remained within budget constraints, with marketing spend showing the largest variance at 8% under allocation due to postponed campaign launches.</p><p>Cash flow analysis reveals positive trends in accounts receivable turnover, decreasing from 45 days to 38 days on average. However, inventory carrying costs have increased by 12% due to supply chain adjustments. The finance team recommends reviewing vendor contracts in Q2 to optimize payment terms. Preliminary EBITDA stands at $1.1M, representing a 22% margin. Board approval is required before these figures can be considered final, pending complete reconciliation of intercompany transactions.</p>', 'DRAFT', 1, '2026-01-10 09:00:00'),
(2, 1, 2, 'Updated financial report with corrected revenue figures', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report - Corrected Revenue Figures</h1><p>Following the discovery of calculation errors in the previous draft, revenue figures have been recalculated and adjusted. The corrected total revenue stands at $4.5M, representing a 23% quarter-over-quarter growth. The enterprise software division contributed $2.1M of this total, while professional services added $1.4M. The remaining $1.0M came from legacy product lines and maintenance contracts. These corrections stem from properly accounting for multi-year contracts that were previously recognized incorrectly on a cash rather than accrual basis.</p><p>Gross margin has been revised to 58%, down from the initially reported 62%, due to higher cloud infrastructure costs that were not fully allocated in the first draft. Operating income now shows $980,000 compared to the previous $1.2M estimate. The finance team has implemented additional validation controls to prevent such discrepancies in future reporting cycles. An external audit of Q1 processes is recommended to ensure no other systematic errors exist in revenue recognition procedures across other business units.</p>', 'PENDING', 2, '2026-01-12 10:30:00'),
(3, 1, 3, 'Final Q1 financial report approved by finance', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report - Final Approved Version</h1><p>This final report represents the complete and audited financial results for Q1 2026. Total revenue of $4.52M exceeded initial projections by 7.6%, driven by unexpected demand in the Asia-Pacific region. Net income after all adjustments and tax provisions stands at $892,000, yielding earnings per share of $0.18. All figures have been reviewed by external auditors and received unqualified opinions. The finance committee has formally approved these results for release to shareholders and regulatory bodies as required by SEC guidelines.</p><p>Key variances from budget include favorable sales performance in the SMB segment (+18% vs forecast) and unfavorable currency exchange impacts (-3% due to euro weakness). The balance sheet remains strong with $3.2M in cash reserves and no outstanding debt. The board has authorized a $500,000 share repurchase program based on these results. Management will present a detailed Q2 forecast at the upcoming shareholder meeting scheduled for March 15th, incorporating lessons learned from Q1 performance metrics.</p>', 'APPROVED', 3, '2026-01-15 14:00:00'),
(4, 2, 1, 'Initial project proposal for new CRM system', '<h1>CRM System Implementation - Initial Proposal</h1><p>This proposal outlines the business case for replacing our legacy customer relationship management platform with a modern cloud-based solution. Current systems are operating at 85% capacity with increasing performance degradation during peak usage hours. Customer support response times have increased by 40% year-over-year due to inefficient data retrieval processes. A new CRM would consolidate customer data across sales, marketing, and support teams into a single source of truth, eliminating current data silos that cause reporting delays of up to three business days.</p><p>The proposed solution includes Salesforce Sales Cloud with custom integrations to our existing ERP system. Estimated implementation timeline spans 16 weeks with a total budget of $450,000 including licensing, configuration, training, and data migration. Expected ROI includes a 25% reduction in sales administrative time, 30% faster case resolution in support, and improved forecasting accuracy from 65% to 85%. The project requires immediate approval to secure Q2 implementation slots with the vendor.</p>', 'DRAFT', 4, '2026-01-11 08:00:00'),
(5, 2, 2, 'Revised CRM proposal with budget breakdown', '<h1>CRM Proposal - Revised with Budget Details</h1><p>Based on initial stakeholder feedback, this revision provides a detailed line-item budget breakdown for the CRM implementation project. Software licensing accounts for $180,000 over three years, professional services for implementation total $150,000, training costs are estimated at $45,000, and ongoing maintenance reserves add $75,000. The finance team has reviewed these figures and confirmed alignment with departmental budget allocations for technology modernization initiatives previously approved for fiscal year 2026.</p><p>Additional considerations now include data cleansing requirements estimated at 200 hours of contractor time ($20,000) and change management activities ($30,000) to ensure user adoption. The revised total of $500,000 includes a 10% contingency buffer for unforeseen technical challenges. A phased rollout approach is recommended, starting with the sales department in month one, followed by support in month two, and marketing in month three. This strategy minimizes business disruption while allowing for iterative learning and adjustments.</p>', 'PENDING', 5, '2026-01-13 11:00:00'),
(6, 2, 3, 'CRM proposal after stakeholder feedback', '<h1>CRM Proposal - Post-Stakeholder Feedback Revision</h1><p>Stakeholder feedback from department heads has identified several critical concerns requiring addressal in this revision. The sales team requires mobile offline access capabilities not included in the base proposal, adding $15,000 in licensing costs. Marketing has requested advanced analytics features for campaign tracking, increasing the budget by another $12,000. Support leadership expressed concerns about integration complexity with existing telephony systems, necessitating additional development work estimated at 80 hours ($16,000). These requirements were previously undocumented in the requirements gathering phase.</p><p>Despite these additions, the project remains viable with a revised budget of $543,000. However, the timeline extends to 20 weeks due to the additional integration work. Some stakeholders have questioned whether a phased approach might better accommodate these requirements while controlling costs. The project sponsor recommends rejecting this version and reconvening requirements gathering sessions to prioritize features and potentially descope non-critical functionality to maintain budget and timeline targets originally established by executive leadership.</p>', 'REJECTED', 6, '2026-01-16 09:30:00'),
(7, 2, 4, 'Final CRM proposal v4', '<h1>Final CRM Proposal - Version 4</h1><p>This final proposal incorporates all stakeholder feedback and represents the consensus-approved approach for CRM implementation. Following the rejection of version 3, the project team facilitated three additional requirements workshops resulting in prioritized feature sets. Core mandatory features include sales pipeline management, support ticketing integration, and marketing campaign tracking. Nice-to-have features such as mobile offline access and advanced analytics will be deferred to phase 2 implementation in Q3 2026. This descoping reduces the budget to $475,000 and maintains the original 16-week timeline.</p><p>Executive sponsorship has been confirmed with the CTO serving as executive sponsor and the VP of Sales as business owner. Governance includes weekly steering committee meetings and bi-weekly status reporting to the board. The vendor has provided a fixed-price contract with penalties for missed milestones. Change control procedures require formal approval for any scope modifications. This proposal awaits final approval from the capital expenditure committee scheduled to meet on January 25th. Upon approval, implementation can commence February 1st.</p>', 'APPROVED', 7, '2026-01-18 13:00:00'),
(8, 3, 1, 'Employee handbook draft - remote work policy', '<h1>Employee Handbook - Remote Work Policy Draft</h1><p>This draft section of the employee handbook establishes guidelines for remote work arrangements effective Q2 2026. Employees may request remote work status for up to five days per week, subject to manager approval and role suitability. Positions requiring on-site presence such as facilities, IT hardware support, and executive assistants are not eligible for full-time remote status. Remote employees must maintain a dedicated home office space meeting ergonomic safety standards, including adjustable chairs, proper lighting, and reliable high-speed internet connection of at least 50 Mbps download speed.</p><p>Accountability measures include daily check-ins via company communication platforms, weekly team meetings requiring camera-on participation, and monthly in-person attendance at team days. Equipment provided includes laptops, monitors, keyboards, and mice, while employees are responsible for desks, chairs, and internet connectivity. A $500 stipend is available for home office setup upon approval. Remote work agreements are valid for six months and require renewal with updated manager evaluation. Violations of data security policies while remote may result in revocation of remote privileges.</p>', 'DRAFT', 8, '2026-01-12 09:00:00'),
(9, 3, 2, 'Updated handbook including hybrid work guidelines', '<h1>Employee Handbook - Hybrid Work Guidelines</h1><p>This update expands the previous draft to include specific hybrid work models accommodating different team needs. Three hybrid tiers are now defined: Remote-First (1-2 office days monthly), Balanced (2-3 office days weekly), and Office-First (4-5 office days weekly). Department heads determine appropriate tiers based on role requirements, with individual appeals possible through HR review. The hybrid model replaces the previously proposed full remote option, recognizing the value of in-person collaboration for innovation and team cohesion based on recent internal surveys showing 73% employee preference for hybrid arrangements.</p><p>Office attendance tracking will utilize badge swipe data and Wi-Fi connection logs to ensure compliance with tier requirements. Employees below 80% attendance targets will receive coaching, followed by performance improvement plans for continued non-compliance. Exceptions exist for medical accommodations approved by HR with proper documentation. Hoteling systems will reserve workspace for hybrid employees, ensuring no dedicated desk assignments except for Office-First tier staff. Managers receive training on equitable treatment of remote and in-office team members to prevent proximity bias in promotion decisions.</p>', 'PENDING', 9, '2026-01-14 10:00:00'),
(10, 3, 3, 'HR approved employee handbook 2026', '<h1>Employee Handbook 2026 - HR Approved Final Version</h1><p>This fully approved employee handbook supersedes all previous versions and becomes effective March 1, 2026. Key policies include the hybrid work framework described in section 4.2, updated paid time off accrual rates (15 days annually for new hires, increasing to 20 days after two years), and revised expense reimbursement procedures requiring manager pre-approval for any single expense exceeding $250. The handbook also introduces new parental leave benefits of 12 weeks fully paid, up from 8 weeks in previous policy, aligning with industry best practices and improving our competitive positioning for talent acquisition.</p><p>All employees must acknowledge receipt and understanding of this handbook through the HR portal by February 28, 2026. Non-acknowledgment will result in suspension of certain system access privileges until compliance is achieved. The handbook has been reviewed by external legal counsel for compliance with all applicable federal, state, and local employment laws, including recent changes to overtime exemption rules and pay transparency requirements. A summary of changes from the 2025 handbook is available as Appendix A. HR will conduct informational sessions during February to address employee questions.</p>', 'APPROVED', 10, '2026-01-17 16:00:00'),
(11, 4, 1, 'Marketing strategy for product launch', '<h1>Product Launch Marketing Strategy - Initial Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the go-to-market strategy for Project Phoenix, our flagship product launching in Q2 2026. Target audience segments include enterprise IT decision-makers (primary) and mid-market technical buyers (secondary). Messaging pillars focus on three key differentiators: 40% faster deployment compared to competitors, AI-powered automation reducing manual tasks by 60%, and enterprise-grade security with SOC2 Type II certification achieved in December 2025. Launch date is tentatively scheduled for April 15th, pending final product readiness certification from engineering.</p><p>Marketing channels include paid search (Google Ads targeting competitor keywords), content syndication through TechTarget and IDG, and a coordinated email campaign to our existing customer base of 5,000 contacts. Total budget allocation is $350,000 with expected reach of 250,000 unique prospects and lead generation target of 2,500 marketing-qualified leads. Success metrics include cost per lead ($140 target), conversion rate to opportunity (15% target), and pipeline contribution ($5M target). A soft launch to existing customers is planned for March 25th to gather early testimonials.</p>', 'DRAFT', 1, '2026-01-13 08:30:00'),
(12, 4, 2, 'Marketing strategy with social media plan', '<h1>Marketing Strategy - Social Media Plan Added</h1><p>This revision adds a comprehensive social media component to the launch strategy based on CMO direction. LinkedIn will serve as the primary platform with sponsored content, thought leadership articles from executives, and targeted InMail campaigns to IT decision-makers. Budget allocation for social now totals $120,000 of the $350,000 overall, including $40,000 for LinkedIn, $25,000 for Twitter (focusing on developer communities), $15,000 for YouTube ads featuring product demo videos, and $40,000 for influencer partnerships with industry analysts and key opinion leaders in the enterprise software space.</p><p>Organic social content includes weekly blog posts, customer case study releases, and live Q&A sessions with product managers. A social listening strategy will monitor brand mentions and competitor activity, with daily reports to the marketing team during launch week and weekly reports thereafter. The social media manager will coordinate with paid media specialists to ensure consistent messaging across all channels. Key performance indicators for social include engagement rate (2.5% target), share of voice (30% target among key competitors), and click-through rate to landing pages (1.2% target).</p>', 'PENDING', 2, '2026-01-15 11:30:00'),
(13, 4, 3, 'Revised marketing strategy after budget cuts', '<h1>Marketing Strategy - Revised Following Budget Cuts</h1><p>Due to a 30% reduction in marketing budget effective immediately (from $350,000 to $245,000), this revision significantly scales back planned activities while attempting to preserve core launch capabilities. The enterprise paid search program is eliminated entirely, saving $60,000 but reducing expected reach by an estimated 40%. Social media spend reduces to $70,000 by eliminating influencer partnerships and YouTube ads, focusing only on LinkedIn and organic Twitter activities. Content syndication partners are reduced from three to one (TechTarget only), saving $25,000.</p><p>Email marketing to the existing customer base remains fully funded as this channel historically provides the highest ROI (average 5:1). The reduced budget forces a 25% reduction in lead generation targets (now 1,875 MQLs) and a 30% reduction in pipeline contribution expectation (now $3.5M). The VP of Marketing has expressed concern that these cuts may jeopardize launch success metrics. An alternative proposal suggests delaying launch by 60 days to preserve original scope while seeking additional funding from the CFO. This version is submitted for executive review with risk assessment attached.</p>', 'REJECTED', 3, '2026-01-18 09:00:00'),
(14, 4, 4, 'Final lean marketing strategy', '<h1>Final Lean Marketing Strategy - Approved Version</h1><p>This approved strategy represents a compromise between the original scope and budget-cut version. Total budget is set at $290,000, achieved by eliminating the content syndication program entirely (-$45,000) while restoring enterprise paid search at reduced spend (-$30,000 from original). Social media maintains LinkedIn ads but removes Twitter and YouTube (-$40,000). The remaining $20,000 reduction comes from decreased agency fees by bringing creative development in-house. The CFO has approved this budget with the condition that ROI tracking be reported weekly during the first month of launch.</p><p>Lead generation targets are revised to 2,100 MQLs with an expected pipeline of $4.2M. To compensate for reduced paid channels, the team will implement an aggressive referral program offering $500 Amazon gift cards for customer referrals that result in qualified meetings. Additionally, the sales development team will receive additional headcount (one SDR) funded by the budget savings to conduct outbound prospecting to accounts previously targeted by content syndication. Launch date remains April 15th. The CMO has approved this strategy contingent upon monthly budget reviews with flexibility to shift funds between channels based on performance data.</p>', 'APPROVED', 4, '2026-01-20 14:00:00'),
(15, 5, 1, 'Security audit report - initial findings', '<h1>Security Audit Report - Initial Findings</h1><p>This preliminary security audit report documents findings from the January 2026 assessment of corporate IT infrastructure. The audit covered 250 servers, 1,200 workstations, and 15 cloud applications across AWS and Azure environments. Critical findings include 12 unpatched servers with known CVEs rated 7.5 or higher, 45 employee accounts with excessive permissions violating least-privilege principles, and 3 databases containing PII without encryption at rest. The most severe vulnerability (CVE-2025-12345 affecting Apache Log4j) remains unpatched on 8 production systems despite patches being available for 90 days.</p><p>Additionally, the audit identified 250 instances of weak password configurations not meeting complexity requirements, 15 active vendor accounts that should have been deactivated after project completion, and lack of MFA on 30% of administrative accounts. Compliance gaps include violation of GDPR Article 32 (security of processing) and potential HIPAA breaches if affected systems handle PHI. The security team recommends immediate remediation of critical findings within 7 days, high-severity issues within 30 days, and medium-severity within 90 days. Executive summary presentation is scheduled for January 20th.</p>', 'DRAFT', 5, '2026-01-14 10:00:00'),
(16, 5, 2, 'Security audit with vulnerability fixes', '<h1>Security Audit - Vulnerability Fixes Applied</h1><p>This updated report reflects remediation efforts completed following the initial audit findings. All 12 unpatched servers with critical CVEs have been patched as of January 18th, including the Log4j vulnerability across all 8 affected production systems. Excessive permissions have been reduced for 40 of the 45 identified accounts, with the remaining 5 requiring further business justification review scheduled for completion by January 25th. Database encryption has been implemented for the 3 previously unencrypted PII databases using AWS KMS with keys rotated every 90 days as per security policy requirements.</p><p>Weak password configurations have been addressed through updated Group Policy Objects enforcing 12-character minimum, complexity requirements, and password history of 24 previous passwords. MFA has been enabled for all administrative accounts (100% compliance achieved January 19th). Vendor accounts remain under review with access reviews scheduled monthly. The security team has reduced overall risk exposure from \"High\" to \"Medium\" based on remediation progress. Remaining open items include the 5 excessive permission accounts and completion of vendor access reviews. A follow-up audit is scheduled for February 15th to validate full remediation.</p>', 'PENDING', 6, '2026-01-16 13:00:00'),
(17, 5, 3, 'Security audit final approved version', '<h1>Security Audit Final Report - Approved Version</h1><p>This final security audit report confirms full remediation of all findings identified in the January 2026 assessment. All 45 excessive permission accounts have been reviewed and adjusted, with 40 reduced in scope and 5 terminated due to role changes. Vendor access reviews completed for all 15 active vendor accounts, resulting in 8 access reductions and 3 account terminations where vendors no longer required system access. Database encryption validation confirms all PII databases now encrypt data at rest with proper key management controls in place. The security posture has improved from a baseline score of 62/100 to 89/100 based on CIS benchmark criteria.</p><p>The audit team recommends ongoing monthly vulnerability scans, quarterly penetration testing, and annual third-party audits to maintain this improved security posture. Additionally, the organization should implement a formal vulnerability management program with SLAs for patch deployment (critical: 48 hours, high: 7 days, medium: 30 days). The CISO has accepted all residual risks, including the 5 terminated accounts (risk accepted due to employee departures) and the minor delay in MFA implementation for service accounts (scheduled for Q2). This report is approved for board distribution and compliance reporting to relevant regulatory bodies including SOC2 auditors.</p>', 'APPROVED', 7, '2026-01-19 11:00:00'),
(18, 6, 1, 'Q2 sales forecast draft', '<h1>Q2 Sales Forecast - Initial Draft</h1><p>This draft forecast projects Q2 2026 sales performance based on historical data, pipeline analysis, and market conditions. Total projected revenue is $5.2M, representing 15% growth over Q1 actuals of $4.52M. The enterprise segment contributes $2.8M (54% of total), mid-market adds $1.6M (31%), and SMB accounts for $0.8M (15%). Key drivers include the launch of Project Phoenix (estimated $1.2M in new bookings), expansion opportunities in existing enterprise accounts ($0.9M), and seasonal uplift in the education sector due to budget flush in June ($0.4M). These projections assume no major economic disruptions and continued sales team headcount at current levels.</p><p>Risks to forecast include potential supply chain constraints affecting product availability (estimated 15% probability), increased competition from a new entrant announcing Q2 launch, and sales team attrition (currently running at 12% annualized). Mitigation strategies include safety stock inventory of 30 days beyond forecast, competitive battle cards distributed to all sales reps, and accelerated hiring of two additional enterprise AEs to reduce workload on existing team. The sales operations team recommends a 10% buffer applied to all regional forecasts to account for historical variance of 8-12% in Q2 quarters over the past three years.</p>', 'DRAFT', 8, '2026-01-15 09:00:00'),
(19, 6, 2, 'Q2 sales forecast with regional breakdown', '<h1>Q2 Sales Forecast - Regional Breakdown Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed regional projections to the Q2 forecast. North America leads with $2.7M (52% of total), driven by strong enterprise demand in financial services and healthcare verticals. EMEA contributes $1.4M (27%), with particular strength in DACH region (Germany, Austria, Switzerland) offsetting weakness in Southern Europe due to economic uncertainty. Asia-Pacific adds $0.9M (17%), primarily from Australia and Singapore, while Japan remains below target due to longer sales cycles. Latin America rounds out the forecast at $0.2M (4%), consistent with historical patterns despite currency fluctuation risks noted by the treasury team.</p><p>Regional variances from company average include higher growth in APAC (22% projected vs 15% company average) due to new partnership agreements signed in Q1, and lower growth in EMEA (10% vs 15%) due to anticipated regulatory changes affecting data residency requirements. Sales capacity analysis shows NA at 85% utilization (understaffed by 3 AEs), EMEA at 95% (fully staffed), APAC at 110% (overutilized, requiring headcount addition), and LATAM at 60% (performance improvement needed). Recommendations include transferring two AEs from LATAM to NA and approving one new headcount for APAC. Regional forecasts have been reviewed by respective sales VPs and reflect their committed numbers.</p>', 'PENDING', 9, '2026-01-17 10:00:00'),
(20, 6, 3, 'Q2 sales forecast - executive summary', '<h1>Q2 Sales Forecast - Executive Summary</h1><p>This executive summary version condenses the detailed forecast for leadership review. Total Q2 projection of $5.2M represents a 15% increase over Q1, with the board-requested stretch target of $5.5M deemed achievable but requiring incremental investment in demand generation ($150,000 for additional paid search and events). The forecast incorporates known opportunities with 75% probability weighting, resulting in a weighted pipeline value of $6.1M against the $5.2M target, indicating a 1.17x coverage ratio. The CRO has expressed confidence in the forecast but notes that the stretch target would require converting three additional high-risk opportunities currently at 25% probability.</p><p>Cash flow implications include $1.8M of forecasted Q2 bookings expected to be recognized as revenue in Q3 due to subscription accounting treatment, creating a timing difference that impacts reported revenue but not cash collections. The CFO has requested monthly forecast updates with actual vs projected variance analysis to improve forecasting accuracy for Q3 planning. Key assumptions include stable renewal rates of 92% on existing subscription base ($2.1M in renewal bookings) and no major customer churn events. This version is submitted for board review with the recommendation to maintain the $5.2M target rather than pursuing the stretch goal given current market uncertainties.</p>', 'REJECTED', 10, '2026-01-20 09:30:00'),
(21, 6, 4, 'Final Q2 sales forecast approved', '<h1>Final Q2 Sales Forecast - Approved Version</h1><p>This final approved forecast adopts the $5.3M target as a compromise between the original $5.2M and stretch $5.5M proposals. The board approved this midpoint with the condition that sales leadership provides weekly pipeline reviews during April and May to monitor progress. Regional allocations are revised as follows: NA $2.8M, EMEA $1.4M, APAC $0.9M, LATAM $0.2M. The additional $0.1M over the original forecast comes from identified upside opportunities in the NA enterprise segment, specifically three financial services deals currently in contract negotiation with expected close dates in June.</p><p>Sales incentives have been adjusted to reward achievement of the $5.3M target with accelerators of 1.5x commission for any revenue above target up to $5.8M. The forecast includes a 7% probability-weighted contingency ($371,000) for deals that may slip to Q3, consistent with historical Q2 slippage rates. The sales operations team will implement a new forecasting tool (Clari) effective March 1st to improve visibility and reduce manual data entry. All sales VPs have signed off on their regional commitments. This forecast becomes the official Q2 target against which performance will be measured for commission calculations and quarterly business reviews.</p>', 'APPROVED', 1, '2026-01-22 15:00:00'),
(22, 7, 1, 'Customer support playbook draft', '<h1>Customer Support Playbook - Initial Draft</h1><p>This playbook establishes standardized procedures for the customer support team handling tier 1-3 incidents. Support requests are categorized into severity levels: Sev1 (system down/critical impact) requires response within 15 minutes, Sev2 (major functionality impaired) within 2 hours, Sev3 (minor issue) within 24 hours, and Sev4 (how-to questions) within 48 hours. The playbook includes escalation paths for each severity level, with Sev1 issues requiring immediate notification to the on-call engineering manager and CTO for critical outages affecting more than 10% of the customer base.</p><p>Communication protocols mandate status updates every 30 minutes for Sev1 incidents via email and status page updates. Customer communication templates are provided for each stage of incident resolution, including initial acknowledgment, progress updates, root cause analysis, and post-mortem summaries. The playbook also covers after-hours support rotation schedules, holiday coverage procedures, and compensation guidelines for customers affected by SLA violations. All support team members must complete playbook certification within 30 days of hire, with annual recertification required thereafter.</p>', 'DRAFT', 2, '2026-01-16 08:00:00'),
(23, 7, 2, 'Updated playbook with escalation procedures', '<h1>Customer Support Playbook - Escalation Procedures Added</h1><p>This update significantly expands the escalation procedures section based on feedback from the support management team. A three-tier escalation framework is now defined: Tier 1 (L1 support agent to L2 team lead) triggered when issue exceeds 30 minutes without resolution, Tier 2 (L2 to L3 manager) at 2 hours for Sev1/Sev2 issues, and Tier 3 (L3 to director) at 4 hours requiring executive communication. Each escalation level includes specific handoff documentation requirements, ensuring seamless transfer of customer context without requiring the customer to repeat information across support tiers.</p><p>The playbook now includes detailed decision trees for common escalation scenarios, including database corruption, API outages, security incidents, and data loss events. A mandatory escalation log must be maintained in the ticketing system, capturing timestamps, decisions made, and executive notifications. Monthly escalation review meetings will analyze patterns to identify training opportunities and process improvements. The playbook also introduces a customer advocacy role responsible for managing communications during extended escalations, ensuring consistent messaging and proactive status updates to affected stakeholders.</p>', 'PENDING', 3, '2026-01-18 11:00:00'),
(24, 7, 3, 'Support playbook final version', '<h1>Customer Support Playbook - Final Approved Version</h1><p>This final playbook incorporates all stakeholder feedback and has been approved by the VP of Customer Success for company-wide adoption effective March 1, 2026. Key enhancements include a revised severity matrix with clearer examples for each level, automated escalation triggers within the Zendesk ticketing system, and integration with PagerDuty for on-call notifications. The playbook also introduces customer health scoring based on ticket volume, response times, and satisfaction ratings, enabling proactive outreach to at-risk accounts before issues escalate into churn risks.</p><p>Training requirements have been finalized, including a 40-hour certification program combining e-learning modules, role-playing exercises, and shadow shifts with experienced team members. Quarterly drills will simulate major incidents to test playbook effectiveness and team readiness. The playbook is a living document, with review cycles scheduled for each quarter and a formal annual revision process led by the support operations team. All team members have acknowledged receipt and completed certification as of February 15th. This playbook supersedes all previous versions and training materials.</p>', 'APPROVED', 4, '2026-01-21 13:30:00'),
(25, 8, 1, 'Onboarding checklist for new hires', '<h1>Onboarding Checklist - New Hire Draft</h1><p>This onboarding checklist provides a structured 30-day program for all new employees joining the company. Week 1 focuses on administrative setup: IT account creation, equipment provisioning (laptop, monitor, accessories), security training completion, benefits enrollment, and payroll documentation. The checklist includes specific tasks for the new hire, their manager, HR business partner, and IT support, with clear owners and due dates for each item. A digital version is maintained in the HRIS system with automated reminders sent to task owners three days before each deadline to ensure timely completion.</p><p>Weeks 2-3 cover role-specific training, including product knowledge sessions, departmental process overviews, and shadowing opportunities with experienced team members. Week 4 includes a 30-day check-in meeting with the manager to review progress against learning objectives and address any gaps. The checklist also includes cultural integration activities such as team lunch invitations, company history sessions, and introduction to employee resource groups. Completion of the full checklist is required before the new hire passes probationary period and gains eligibility for performance-based compensation plans.</p>', 'DRAFT', 5, '2026-01-17 09:00:00'),
(26, 8, 2, 'Onboarding checklist with IT and HR tasks', '<h1>Onboarding Checklist - IT and HR Tasks Expanded</h1><p>This revision provides significantly more detail on IT and HR responsibilities within the onboarding process. IT tasks now include specific hardware models (Dell Latitude 5430 for standard users, MacBook Pro for engineering), software license assignments (Microsoft Office, Slack, Zoom, VPN client), and security configurations (endpoint protection, disk encryption, MFA enrollment). A new IT service portal request form automates equipment provisioning, reducing setup time from 5 days to 2 days based on pilot testing with the January 2026 new hire cohort.</p><p>HR tasks now include compliance training assignments (harassment prevention, data privacy, insider trading), benefits orientation scheduling, and I-9 verification procedures for US-based employees. International hires trigger additional tasks including visa sponsorship documentation, tax treaty forms, and local labor law acknowledgments. The checklist also introduces a buddy system pairing each new hire with a tenured employee for informal guidance during the first 90 days. Buddy responsibilities include weekly check-ins, office tour, and introductions to key stakeholders outside the new hire''s immediate team.</p>', 'PENDING', 6, '2026-01-19 10:30:00'),
(27, 8, 3, 'Revised onboarding checklist after team feedback', '<h1>Onboarding Checklist - Revised Post-Feedback</h1><p>Based on feedback from hiring managers and recent new hires, several checklist items have been reordered and clarified. The most significant change moves security training from week 1 to pre-boarding (before start date), reducing first-week cognitive load. Manager feedback indicated that weeks 2-3 were overloaded with training sessions, so the revision spreads technical training across weeks 2-5 and adds buffer time for self-study and hands-on practice with development environments. New hires reported confusion about equipment ordering processes, prompting the addition of clear instructions with screenshots for the IT portal.</p><p>However, some stakeholders expressed concerns that extending the checklist to 5 weeks delays productivity ramp-up. Sales leadership noted that quota-carrying new hires need to be fully productive by week 4 to meet quarterly targets. The revised checklist attempts to balance comprehensive onboarding with business velocity by adding role-specific fast-track options for experienced hires. This version requires further alignment between HR, IT, and department heads before final approval. The project sponsor recommends rejecting this version and convening a working group to resolve the duration disagreement.</p>', 'REJECTED', 7, '2026-01-22 14:00:00'),
(28, 8, 4, 'Final onboarding checklist 2026', '<h1>Final Onboarding Checklist - Approved 2026 Version</h1><p>This approved checklist represents consensus between HR, IT, and department leadership. The program duration is set at 4 weeks with the following structure: Week 1 (Administrative & Compliance), Week 2 (Core Training & Shadowing), Week 3 (Role-Specific Skills), Week 4 (Independent Work & Checkpoints). A fast-track option exists for experienced hires with documented prior experience, reducing week 2-3 training by 40% with manager approval. The checklist includes 62 total tasks, down from 78 in the previous revision, achieved by consolidating duplicate requirements and automating status tracking.</p><p>Implementation begins March 1, 2026, with all existing employees receiving training on their checklist responsibilities by February 25th. The HRIS system has been updated to support automated task assignments and deadline reminders. Completion rates will be tracked as a team KPI for HR business partners, with a target of 95% task completion within 5 days of due dates. The checklist will be reviewed quarterly for the first year, with formal annual updates thereafter. All hiring managers have signed off on this version, and the CFO has approved the $15,000 budget for system enhancements required to support the new process.</p>', 'APPROVED', 8, '2026-01-24 09:00:00'),
(29, 9, 1, 'Annual compliance review part 1', '<h1>Annual Compliance Review - Part 1: Framework Overview</h1><p>This document initiates the annual compliance review process for fiscal year 2026, covering regulatory requirements across all operating jurisdictions. Part 1 establishes the review framework, including applicable regulations (GDPR for European operations, CCPA for California, LGPD for Brazil, PIPEDA for Canada, and sector-specific requirements for financial services and healthcare customers). The review scope encompasses data protection policies, security controls, third-party vendor management, employee training records, and incident response procedures. Each compliance domain has been assigned to an owner responsible for evidence collection and gap analysis completion by March 31, 2026.</p><p>The framework utilizes a maturity model with five levels: Initial (ad-hoc), Managed (documented), Defined (standardized), Quantitatively Managed (measured), and Optimizing (continuous improvement). Current baseline assessments place data protection at Level 2, security controls at Level 3, vendor management at Level 1, training at Level 2, and incident response at Level 2. Part 1 establishes remediation targets of Level 3 for all domains by June 30, 2026, with the exception of vendor management which requires a two-year roadmap to reach Level 3 due to the volume of third-party relationships (currently 250+ active vendors).</p>', 'DRAFT', 9, '2026-01-18 08:00:00'),
(30, 9, 2, 'Compliance review with GDPR updates', '<h1>Annual Compliance Review - GDPR Updates Incorporated</h1><p>This revision incorporates recent GDPR guidance from the European Data Protection Board (EDPB) issued in December 2025. Key updates include new requirements for data protection impact assessments (DPIAs) when using AI/ML systems processing personal data, stricter rules for international data transfers following the revised EU-US Data Privacy Framework, and expanded rights for data subjects including the right to algorithmic explanation. These changes affect three current systems: the CRM (uses AI for lead scoring), the marketing automation platform (processes email engagement data), and the HRIS (stores candidate information from EU applicants).</p><p>Compliance gaps identified include missing DPIAs for the AI features (required by April 30, 2026), outdated standard contractual clauses for 15 vendors transferring EU data, and insufficient documentation of legitimate interests assessments for direct marketing activities. The legal team has been engaged to update privacy policies and consent mechanisms. A remediation budget of $75,000 has been requested for external privacy consultant support and DPIA tooling. The compliance review timeline has been extended to April 30th to accommodate these GDPR-specific requirements, with board updates scheduled for the March and April meetings.</p>', 'PENDING', 10, '2026-01-20 11:00:00'),
(31, 9, 3, 'Compliance review approved by legal', '<h1>Annual Compliance Review - Legal Approved Final</h1><p>This final compliance review has been reviewed and approved by the legal department and external counsel. All GDPR remediation items have been addressed, including DPIAs for AI systems completed March 15th, updated SCCs executed with all 15 vendors, and legitimate interests assessments documented for all marketing activities. CCPA compliance has been enhanced with a new \"Do Not Sell My Info\" page implemented on the company website and a consumer rights request portal deployed in the customer account center. Response time for access/deletion requests has been reduced from 45 days to 15 days through process automation and dedicated privacy team resources.</p><p>Compliance scores have improved across all domains: Data Protection now at Level 3 (up from 2), Security Controls maintained at Level 3, Vendor Management at Level 2 (up from 1), Training at Level 3 (up from 2), and Incident Response at Level 3 (up from 2). The compliance roadmap for 2027 has been drafted, targeting Level 4 for Data Protection and Security Controls through automation of compliance evidence collection. Legal has authorized the compliance officer to conduct unannounced spot audits throughout 2026 to verify ongoing adherence. This report is approved for distribution to the board of directors and relevant regulators as required by our consent decrees.</p>', 'APPROVED', 1, '2026-01-23 16:00:00'),
(32, 10, 1, 'Server migration plan initial', '<h1>Server Migration Plan - Initial Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the migration of 150 on-premise servers to AWS cloud infrastructure over a 12-week period starting April 1, 2026. The migration follows a lift-and-shift approach for the first 100 servers (web servers, application servers, and databases under 2TB), followed by re-platforming for the remaining 50 servers (legacy systems requiring dependency updates). Target environment includes EC2 instances (t3.large for web, r5.xlarge for databases), RDS for managed database services (PostgreSQL 14, MySQL 8.0), and S3 for static content storage. Estimated cloud monthly costs are $45,000 compared to current on-premise operational costs of $38,000, representing a short-term increase of 18% offset by reduced hardware refresh cycles in year 2.</p><p>Migration waves are organized by application criticality and interdependencies. Wave 1 (weeks 1-4) covers non-production environments and development tools. Wave 2 (weeks 5-8) migrates internal business systems (HRIS, expense reporting, document management). Wave 3 (weeks 9-12) addresses customer-facing production systems, scheduled during low-traffic periods (Saturday 12am-6am ET). Rollback procedures are defined for each wave, with a maximum acceptable rollback time of 4 hours. The plan requires approval from the architecture review board and change advisory committee before execution.</p>', 'DRAFT', 2, '2026-01-19 09:00:00'),
(33, 10, 2, 'Migration plan with rollback strategy', '<h1>Server Migration Plan - Rollback Strategy Added</h1><p>This revision adds a comprehensive rollback strategy based on feedback from the infrastructure team. Each migration wave includes a pre-migration snapshot of source systems, configuration backups, and network topology documentation. Rollback triggers include any of the following: error rates exceeding 5% post-migration, latency increases above 200ms (baseline 50ms), data integrity check failures, or security control gaps identified within 24 hours. The rollback procedure involves redirecting traffic to source environment, restoring data from pre-migration backups, and reverting DNS changes, with an expected RTO of 2 hours and RPO of 15 minutes.</p><p>A testing protocol has been established requiring validation of all critical functionality before and after migration. Smoke tests include authentication flows, API endpoints, database queries, and scheduled job execution. Load testing at 150% of peak production traffic validates performance targets. The plan now includes a gating process: no wave proceeds to the next unless all tests pass and the post-migration stability period (72 hours) shows no severity 1 or 2 incidents. A war room will be staffed during each migration window, including representatives from infrastructure, security, applications, and database administration teams with decision authority to execute rollback if triggers are met.</p>', 'PENDING', 3, '2026-01-21 10:00:00'),
(34, 10, 3, 'Updated migration plan - phase 1 only', '<h1>Server Migration Plan - Phase 1 Only (Revised)</h1><p>Following budget review, this revision reduces the migration scope to Phase 1 only (non-production and development environments), deferring production workloads to Q3 2026. The CIO requested this change to reallocate $150,000 in cloud migration funding to the CRM implementation project deemed higher priority by the executive committee. Phase 1 will migrate 35 non-production servers over 6 weeks, providing team experience with AWS tooling (CloudEndure for migration, CloudFormation for infrastructure-as-code) while maintaining current production environment on-premise.</p><p>This reduced scope significantly impacts the expected benefits of the migration. Cloud cost savings are delayed by 6 months, and the organization continues to incur data center operational expenses ($38,000 monthly) plus additional cloud costs for non-production environments ($12,000 monthly), resulting in net negative ROI for 2026. The infrastructure team has expressed concern that maintaining dual environments increases operational complexity and risks configuration drift between production and non-production systems. The project sponsor recommends rejecting this version and seeking restored funding from the CFO, as partial migration may create more problems than it solves.</p>', 'REJECTED', 4, '2026-01-24 13:00:00'),                                                                                              (35, 10, 4, 'Final server migration plan Q2', '<h1>Final Server Migration Plan - Q2 2026</h1><p>This approved migration plan restores full scope with a revised budget of $380,000 (reduced from original $450,000) achieved through negotiated AWS discounts (15% reserved instance commitment) and reduced consulting hours (bringing 30% of migration work in-house). The timeline remains 12 weeks starting April 1st, with all three waves proceeding as originally designed. Executive sponsorship has been confirmed with the CIO as executive sponsor and the infrastructure director as project manager. Monthly steering committee reviews will monitor progress, budget variance, and risk status with escalation triggers for any wave exceeding 10% timeline slippage.</p><p>Post-migration validation includes a 30-day stability period with daily health checks, weekly performance reviews, and a formal go-live announcement only after 14 consecutive days without severity 1 or 2 incidents. The rollback strategy from version 2 is fully incorporated with automated scripts tested during each wave''s dress rehearsal. Training for operations teams on AWS console, CloudWatch monitoring, and incident response procedures will occur during weeks 1-4, with certification required before wave 2 begins. The change advisory committee has approved all migration windows, and customer communications about potential impact during wave 3 will be sent 14 days in advance. This plan is authorized for execution effective immediately.</p>', 'APPROVED', 5, '2026-01-26 14:30:00'),
(36, 1, 4, 'Q1 report addendum - corrected charts', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report Addendum - Corrected Charts</h1><p>This addendum provides corrected visualizations for the Q1 financial report following identification of data visualization errors in the original approved version. Chart 1 (Quarterly Revenue Trend) incorrectly displayed Q4 2025 revenue as $3.9M when actual was $4.1M, affecting the visual representation of growth rates. The corrected chart shows revenue increasing from $4.1M in Q4 to $4.52M in Q1, representing 10.2% growth rather than the originally depicted 15.9%. Chart 3 (Expense Breakdown) misallocated 8% of R&D expenses to G&A due to a categorization error in the source data, now corrected to show R&D at 32% (up from 24%) and G&A at 18% (down from 26%).</p><p>These corrections do not change the absolute financial results reported in the approved version, only the graphical representation of those results. The addendum has been reviewed by the finance team and external auditors to ensure no other visualization errors exist. A note has been added to the official report indicating that corrected charts supersede those in the original version. The board has been notified, and the investor relations team will distribute this addendum to all recipients of the original report. Process improvements have been implemented to prevent similar errors in future reporting cycles, including mandatory dual-review of all charts by both finance and data visualization teams before approval.</p>', 'DRAFT', 6, '2026-01-20 09:00:00'),
(37, 1, 5, 'Q1 report final with all corrections', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report - Final with All Corrections</h1><p>This consolidated version incorporates the addendum corrections into the main report, superseding both version 3 (original approved) and version 4 (addendum). All charts and tables now reflect accurate data visualizations, with corrected revenue trend lines, expense allocations, and regional breakdowns. The narrative text remains unchanged from version 3 as no factual errors were present in the written analysis, only in the supporting graphics. This version has been re-approved by the finance committee and external auditors as the single source of truth for Q1 2026 results.</p><p>Distribution of this corrected report begins immediately to all internal stakeholders, board members, and regulatory bodies that received the original version. The investor relations team will host a special webcast on February 1st to explain the corrections and answer shareholder questions. The finance department has conducted a root cause analysis of the visualization errors, attributing them to a software bug in the reporting tool (Tableau) that has since been patched. No further corrections are anticipated. This version is designated as the official record for audit purposes and will be retained as required by document retention policies.</p>', 'APPROVED', 7, '2026-01-23 11:00:00'),
(38, 2, 5, 'CRM implementation timeline v5', '<h1>CRM Implementation Timeline - Version 5</h1><p>This detailed timeline outlines the 16-week CRM implementation project approved in version 4. The timeline is organized into five phases: Phase 1 (Weeks 1-2): Requirements finalization and environment setup, Phase 2 (Weeks 3-6): Configuration and customization, Phase 3 (Weeks 7-10): Integration development and data migration, Phase 4 (Weeks 11-14): Testing and user acceptance, Phase 5 (Weeks 15-16): Training and go-live preparation. Each phase includes specific deliverables, owner assignments, and approval gates requiring sign-off before proceeding to the next phase to prevent scope creep and schedule slippage.</p><p>Critical path items include custom API integration with the ERP system (weeks 7-9, 120 hours of development), data cleansing and migration of 500,000 records (weeks 8-10, 200 hours of ETL work), and user acceptance testing sign-off from all three departments (sales, marketing, support). Three milestone dates are locked: Go-live preparation complete (July 15th), Production cutover (July 22nd), and Post-launch support period ends (August 19th). The timeline includes 5 days of contingency buffer distributed across phases based on risk assessment (highest buffer in integration and migration phases). The project manager will update this timeline weekly in Microsoft Project, with variance reports submitted to the steering committee every two weeks.</p>', 'DRAFT', 8, '2026-01-21 08:30:00'),
(39, 2, 6, 'CRM rollout plan with training schedule', '<h1>CRM Rollout Plan - Training Schedule Added</h1><p>This revision adds a comprehensive training schedule for end-users and administrators. Training is segmented by role: Sales (40 users, 8 hours of training), Marketing (15 users, 6 hours), Support (25 users, 6 hours), and Administrators (5 users, 16 hours including certification). Delivery methods include instructor-led virtual sessions (recorded for on-demand access), self-paced e-learning modules in our LMS, and office hours with the implementation team. Training will occur during weeks 13-15, with all users required to complete training before receiving production system access.</p><p>The schedule allocates specific dates: Sales training (July 5th-7th, 9am-12pm daily), Marketing training (July 8th, 1pm-4pm), Support training (July 9th-10th, 9am-12pm), and Administrator training (July 1st-2nd, 9am-5pm). Super-user training for 10 power users from each department occurs during week 12, enabling them to provide peer support during go-live. Training effectiveness will be measured through knowledge assessments (80% passing score) and practical exercises completed in a sandbox environment. Users who fail assessments must retake training before access is granted. The training budget of $25,000 covers LMS hosting, facilitator fees, and certification exam costs.</p>', 'PENDING', 9, '2026-01-24 10:00:00'),
(40, 2, 7, 'Final CRM project plan', '<h1>Final CRM Project Plan - Approved Version</h1><p>This final project plan incorporates all feedback from stakeholders and has been approved by the steering committee. The timeline remains 16 weeks with the training schedule from version 6 fully integrated. Key changes from version 5 include additional integration testing (increased by 5 days) and extended user acceptance testing (from 2 weeks to 3 weeks) based on lessons learned from the ERP implementation last year. The go-live date has shifted from July 22nd to July 29th to accommodate the extended testing period, with post-launch support extended to September 2nd.</p><p>Risk management strategies include daily standups during critical path activities, weekly risk register reviews, and a dedicated issue tracking log. The project budget remains $475,000 with a 5% contingency ($23,750) unallocated for unforeseen issues. Success criteria include system uptime of 99.9% during the first 30 days, user adoption rate of 85% (measured by login frequency and data entry completion), and data accuracy of 98% compared to source systems. The change management plan includes weekly communications, executive sponsorship visibility, and a recognition program for early adopters. All resource commitments have been confirmed by department heads, and the vendor has signed the final statement of work. Project execution begins February 1st.</p>', 'APPROVED', 10, '2026-01-27 13:00:00'),
(41, 3, 4, 'Remote work equipment policy', '<h1>Remote Work Equipment Policy - Draft</h1><p>This policy defines equipment provisioning standards for remote and hybrid employees effective April 1, 2026. Standard equipment package includes company-issued laptop (Windows or Mac based on role), 24-inch external monitor, keyboard, mouse, laptop bag, and USB headset. Employees approved for full-time remote status (5 days per week remote) receive an additional $500 stipend for office furniture (desk, chair, lighting) and $50 monthly internet reimbursement. Hybrid employees (2-3 office days weekly) receive the standard package but no furniture stipend or internet reimbursement, as they are expected to use office facilities for the majority of their work.</p><p>Equipment return requirements mandate that all company-issued equipment be returned within 5 business days of employment separation. Remote employees moving to a different address must notify IT for security assessment of the new location, particularly regarding network security and physical access controls. Equipment damage due to normal wear and tear is covered at no cost to the employee, while damage due to negligence (liquid spills, drops, improper storage) may result in repair charges up to $500. The policy has been reviewed by legal for compliance with state reimbursement laws in CA, IL, NY, and WA where remote employees are concentrated.</p>', 'DRAFT', 1, '2026-01-22 09:00:00'),
(42, 3, 5, 'Updated equipment policy with budget limits', '<h1>Remote Work Equipment Policy - Budget Limits Added</h1><p>This revision adds specific budget limits to the equipment policy following CFO review. The furniture stipend is now capped at $500 per employee with approved vendors (IKEA, Amazon Business, Wayfair Pro) and requires itemized receipts for reimbursement. Internet reimbursement is capped at $50 monthly with proof of service required (billing statement showing employee name and address). Departmental budgets for equipment have been allocated: Sales $25,000, Engineering $40,000, Marketing $15,000, Support $10,000, G&A $8,000. Managers must approve any equipment request exceeding $1,000 total value, with CIO approval required for requests exceeding $2,500.</p><p>The policy now includes a hardware refresh schedule: laptops replaced every 3 years, monitors every 5 years, and peripherals on an as-needed basis. Employees may request upgrades (e.g., larger monitor, premium laptop) with manager approval and cost difference paid from departmental budgets rather than the central equipment fund. A centralized equipment tracking database will be implemented in the IT service management tool, with employees required to update asset locations when moving between remote and office work. The finance team has requested quarterly reporting on equipment spend vs budget, with variance greater than 10% requiring corrective action plans.</p>', 'PENDING', 2, '2026-01-25 14:00:00'),
(43, 3, 6, 'Final remote work policy', '<h1>Final Remote Work Policy - Approved Version</h1><p>This final policy incorporates budget limits from version 5 and has been approved by executive leadership effective April 1, 2026. Key provisions include standard equipment for all employees regardless of work arrangement, with additional $500 furniture stipend and $50 monthly internet reimbursement for full-time remote employees only (defined as 4+ days remote per week). Hybrid employees (2-3 office days) receive no stipend or internet reimbursement but may request occasional home office equipment on a case-by-case basis with director approval. The policy also establishes a Remote Work Agreement that all remote employees must sign, acknowledging their responsibilities for home office safety, data protection, and availability during working hours.</p><p>Implementation responsibilities: HR will update the employee handbook and remote work agreement templates, IT will publish equipment request procedures in the service portal, and Finance will establish reimbursement workflows in the expense system. All current remote employees will have 60 days to comply with the new policy, including signing updated agreements and providing documentation for internet reimbursement claims. New remote hires will follow the policy effective immediately. The policy will be reviewed annually, with the first review scheduled for Q1 2027. Non-compliance may result in revocation of remote work privileges or disciplinary action up to and including termination for repeated violations of data security requirements.</p>', 'APPROVED', 3, '2026-01-28 10:00:00'),
(44, 4, 5, 'Launch event planning document', '<h1>Launch Event Planning Document - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the logistics for the Project Phoenix virtual launch event scheduled for April 15, 2026. The 90-minute event includes a 20-minute keynote from the CEO, 30-minute product demonstration by the Head of Product, 15-minute customer panel featuring three beta testers, and 25-minute Q&A session moderated by the CMO. The event will be hosted on the Hopin platform with capacity for 2,000 attendees. Registration opens March 15th with promotional emails to our customer database of 5,000 contacts and paid social campaigns targeting 50,000 IT decision-makers.</p><p>Production requirements include a virtual studio setup at headquarters (lighting, professional cameras, teleprompter), technical rehearsal on April 14th, and live captioning for accessibility. The event budget is $45,000 covering platform licensing ($5,000), production crew ($15,000), promotional spend ($20,000), and contingency ($5,000). Success metrics include 1,000+ attendees, 70% attendance rate among registrants, average viewing time of 60+ minutes, and 200+ marketing-qualified leads generated from post-event follow-up. A recording will be available on-demand for 30 days after the live event, with highlights edited for social media distribution.</p>', 'DRAFT', 4, '2026-01-23 08:00:00'),
(45, 4, 6, 'Event plan with vendor contracts', '<h1>Launch Event Plan - Vendor Contracts Added</h1><p>This revision adds vendor contracts and production details to the event plan. Signed contracts include Hopin (platform, $5,000), AV production company (Creative Technologies, $15,000 for 3 cameras, director, audio engineer, graphics package), and captioning service (Rev, $1,500 for live captioning and post-event transcript). The promotional budget has been increased to $25,000 following CMO approval, with specific allocations: LinkedIn ads ($12,000), Twitter ads ($5,000), Google display ($5,000), and email marketing platform ($3,000). Contract terms include cancellation policies (50% refund if canceled less than 14 days before event) and force majeure clauses covering pandemic-related restrictions.</p><p>Production schedule now includes: April 10th - Speaker rehearsals, April 12th - Full technical run-through, April 14th - Dress rehearsal with all speakers, April 15th - Live event (10am PT/1pm ET). Backup plans include pre-recorded segments for each speaker in case of technical issues, a secondary platform (Zoom Webinar) if Hopin experiences downtime, and a contingency speaker if any panelist has last-minute conflicts. All speakers have signed release forms authorizing recording and distribution of their presentations. The legal team has reviewed all contracts, and the procurement department has issued purchase orders. Event insurance has been secured with $2M liability coverage.</p>', 'PENDING', 5, '2026-01-26 11:00:00'),
(46, 4, 7, 'Final launch event strategy', '<h1>Final Launch Event Strategy - Approved Version</h1><p>This final event plan incorporates all vendor contracts and production details from version 6, with final budget approved at $50,000 (additional $5,000 for post-event lead nurture campaign). The event date is confirmed for April 15, 2026, 10am-11:30am PT. Key performance indicators have been refined: 1,200+ attendees, 75% attendance rate, 65+ minute average viewing time, 250+ MQLs, and $500,000 in influenced pipeline within 30 days post-event. A post-event survey will measure Net Promoter Score (target +50) and intent to purchase (target 20% of respondents indicating \"very likely\" to evaluate Project Phoenix).</p><p>Executive approval has been received from the CMO and CFO, with weekly status updates required to the marketing leadership team. The event team includes a dedicated project manager, production lead, content manager, and promotional specialist. Risk mitigation includes a recorded backup of all segments, a 15-minute buffer in the agenda for technical issues, and a post-event help desk for attendees experiencing access problems. The event will be promoted through owned channels (email, blog, social) and paid channels (LinkedIn, Google, industry newsletters) with a total estimated reach of 250,000. Registration closes April 14th at 5pm PT. This plan is authorized for execution effective immediately.</p>', 'APPROVED', 6, '2026-01-29 15:00:00'),
(47, 5, 4, 'Security remediation roadmap', '<h1>Security Remediation Roadmap - Draft</h1><p>This roadmap outlines the 90-day plan to address findings from the January 2026 security audit. Priorities are categorized by severity: Critical items (patch management, MFA enforcement, database encryption) must be completed within 30 days. High-severity items (excessive permissions, vendor access reviews) within 60 days. Medium-severity items (password policy updates, logging improvements) within 90 days. Each remediation item includes owner assignment, technical approach, validation method, and success criteria. The roadmap has been reviewed by the security team and CISO for feasibility within existing staffing levels.</p><p>Resource requirements include 400 hours of security engineering time, 200 hours of system administration, and 100 hours of compliance coordination. Budget impact is estimated at $75,000 for software tools (vulnerability scanner upgrade, SIEM enhancements) and $25,000 for external penetration testing to validate remediation. The roadmap assumes no new critical vulnerabilities are discovered during the remediation period, which the security team acknowledges as optimistic given the dynamic threat landscape. Weekly status reporting to the IT leadership team is required, with monthly updates to the board''s audit committee. The CISO will sign off on each completed remediation item after validation.</p>', 'DRAFT', 7, '2026-01-24 09:30:00'),
(48, 5, 5, 'Remediation plan with deadlines', '<h1>Security Remediation Plan - Deadlines Added</h1><p>This revision adds specific deadlines and milestones to the remediation roadmap. Critical items deadlines: All 12 unpatched servers (Jan 31st), MFA for remaining service accounts (Feb 15th), Database encryption validation (Feb 10th). High-severity deadlines: Excessive permission review (Feb 20th), Vendor access attestations (Feb 28th), Password policy GPO deployment (Feb 25th). Medium-severity deadlines: Centralized logging implementation (Mar 15th), Vulnerability scan schedule (weekly starting Feb 1st), Security awareness training for all employees (Mar 31st). Each deadline includes a 5-day grace period for unforeseen technical issues, after which escalation to the CISO is required.</p><p>A project tracker has been created in Jira with automated reminders and dashboard reporting. Remediation owners must update status weekly, with red/yellow/green status indicators: Green (on track), Yellow (at risk, mitigation plan in place), Red (behind schedule, executive attention required). The first milestone review is scheduled for February 5th with the IT leadership team. A remediation validation plan includes automated scanning for patch compliance, quarterly penetration testing, and annual third-party audits. The roadmap now includes a 15% buffer for resource hours to accommodate unexpected complexity. The CISO has approved this version pending final budget review by the CFO.</p>', 'PENDING', 8, '2026-01-27 10:00:00'),
(49, 5, 6, 'Final security roadmap Q2-Q3', '<h1>Final Security Roadmap - Q2-Q3 2026</h1><p>This approved security roadmap extends the remediation plan through Q3 2026 based on CISO direction. Critical and high-severity items from the audit remain on track for Q1 completion as detailed in version 5. New Q2 initiatives include: implementing a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system ($50,000 budget), conducting tabletop incident response exercises (April and June), and achieving SOC2 Type II certification (target July 31st). Q3 initiatives include: deploying endpoint detection and response (EDR) to all 1,200 workstations ($30,000), implementing data loss prevention (DLP) for sensitive data ($40,000), and completing a purple team exercise (simulated attack with blue team defense).</p><p>The total roadmap budget is $220,000 approved by the CFO, with quarterly reviews to assess progress and adjust priorities based on threat intelligence. Success metrics include reducing mean time to detect (MTTD) from 48 hours to 4 hours, reducing mean time to respond (MTTR) from 24 hours to 2 hours, and maintaining vulnerability remediation SLAs (critical: 48 hours, high: 7 days, medium: 30 days). The security team will grow from 5 to 8 FTEs to support these initiatives, with three new hires (SIEM engineer, security analyst, GRC specialist) targeted for Q2 start dates. This roadmap is authorized for execution and will be presented to the board audit committee on February 10th.</p>', 'APPROVED', 9, '2026-01-30 13:00:00'),
(50, 6, 5, 'Sales forecast by product line', '<h1>Q2 Sales Forecast - By Product Line</h1><p>This detailed forecast breaks down the $5.3M Q2 target by product line and customer segment. Product line contributions: Project Phoenix (new product) $1.8M (34%), Core Platform $2.2M (42%), Professional Services $0.7M (13%), Maintenance & Support $0.6M (11%). Within Core Platform, enterprise licenses account for $1.4M, mid-market $0.6M, and SMB $0.2M. Project Phoenix revenue is split between new customer acquisition ($1.2M) and upsells to existing customers ($0.6M). Professional services revenue includes implementation ($0.5M) and training ($0.2M), with a 65% attach rate to new software licenses.</p><p>Product line forecasts incorporate specific assumptions: Project Phoenix assumes 40 new customers at average deal size of $30,000 (enterprise $50,000, mid-market $20,000, SMB $10,000). Core Platform assumes 92% renewal rate on existing base ($1.8M) plus $0.4M in net new business. Professional services assume 250 billable hours per week at average rate of $200/hour. Maintenance assumes 18% of software license value annually. Sales compensation has been aligned with product line priorities, with higher commission rates (12% vs standard 8%) for Project Phoenix to incentivize new product focus. The forecast will be reviewed weekly by product line owners during Q2, with adjustments made monthly based on actual performance and pipeline changes.</p>', 'DRAFT', 10, '2026-01-25 08:00:00'),
(51, 6, 6, 'Updated sales forecast with new product launch', '<h1>Q2 Sales Forecast - New Product Launch Integrated</h1><p>This revision integrates the Project Phoenix launch forecast with the overall sales forecast following final product pricing and packaging decisions. Project Phoenix now has three editions: Professional ($25,000/year), Enterprise ($50,000/year), and Ultimate ($100,000/year). The launch forecast is adjusted to $2.0M (up from $1.8M) based on higher-than-expected interest from early access program (200 companies signed up vs 150 projected). However, the Core Platform forecast is reduced to $2.0M (down from $2.2M) due to expected cannibalization as some existing customers may defer Core Platform upgrades in favor of Project Phoenix.</p><p>Net effect on total forecast is unchanged at $5.3M, but product mix shifts with higher new product revenue and lower legacy product revenue. Professional Services forecast increases to $0.8M (up from $0.7M) due to implementation services for Project Phoenix customers. Maintenance forecast decreases to $0.5M (down from $0.6M) as some customers may not renew maintenance on legacy products they plan to replace with Project Phoenix. The sales team has been trained on the new product line positioning, with competitive displacement scripts for scenarios where customers compare Project Phoenix with legacy offerings. The updated forecast requires approval from product management and finance before integration into official Q2 targets.</p>', 'PENDING', 1, '2026-01-28 14:00:00'),
(52, 6, 7, 'Final Q2 sales forecast v7', '<h1>Final Q2 Sales Forecast - Version 7</h1><p>This approved forecast incorporates the new product launch adjustments from version 6 with final numbers confirmed by the sales leadership team. Total Q2 target remains $5.3M with the following product line breakdown: Project Phoenix $2.0M, Core Platform $2.0M, Professional Services $0.8M, Maintenance $0.5M. The sales operations team has updated commission plans, territory assignments, and quota setting to reflect the new product mix. All regional VPs have signed off on their updated targets, with NA at $2.8M, EMEA $1.4M, APAC $0.9M, LATAM $0.2M as previously approved.</p><p>The forecast includes a sensitivity analysis showing best case ($6.0M) if Project Phoenix exceeds expectations and worst case ($4.5M) if launch is delayed or competitive response is stronger than anticipated. Key assumptions have been documented: no major economic downturn, successful product launch execution, sales headcount fully staffed by March 15th, and renewal rates stable at 92%. The board has approved the forecast with the condition that management provides monthly variance analysis and revised projections for Q3 by May 15th. This forecast is now the official target for Q2 performance measurement, commission calculations, and investor communications.</p>', 'APPROVED', 2, '2026-01-31 11:30:00'),
(53, 7, 4, 'Customer escalation matrix', '<h1>Customer Escalation Matrix - Draft</h1><p>This document defines the escalation matrix for customer issues requiring management involvement. The matrix maps issue types to escalation paths and decision authorities. Technical escalations (product bugs, performance degradation, data loss) route through Engineering management, with the VP of Engineering notified for Sev1 issues affecting >10% of customers. Commercial escalations (billing disputes, contract negotiations, SLA credit requests) route through Sales management, with the VP of Sales notified for issues involving >$100k annual contract value. Operational escalations (support delays, communication failures, process breakdowns) route through Customer Success management, with the VP of Customer Success notified for repeat issues across multiple customers.</p><p>Each escalation path includes defined response SLAs: Initial response within 1 hour, root cause identification within 4 hours (technical) or 24 hours (commercial/operational), and resolution plan within 8 hours (technical) or 48 hours (commercial/operational). Escalation authority includes the ability to approve credits (up to $10k for managers, $50k for VPs, unlimited for C-suite), authorize engineering resources (up to 5 engineers for managers, 20 for VPs), and commit to public communication timelines. The matrix requires training for all support managers and quarterly tabletop exercises to ensure readiness. A digital version will be integrated into the ticketing system to automate escalation triggers based on issue severity and duration.</p>', 'DRAFT', 3, '2026-01-26 09:00:00'),
(54, 7, 5, 'Escalation matrix with SLAs', '<h1>Customer Escalation Matrix - SLAs Added</h1><p>This revision adds specific SLAs and escalation thresholds to the matrix. Escalation triggers are now quantified: Tier 1 to Tier 2 escalation occurs automatically at 30 minutes without customer update, Tier 2 to Tier 3 at 2 hours without resolution plan, Tier 3 to executive at 4 hours without customer-approved resolution. SLA timers pause only when awaiting customer response, with a 24-hour maximum pause before automatic escalation resumes. The matrix includes a customer communication SLA requiring updates every 30 minutes for Sev1, 2 hours for Sev2, and daily for Sev3/Sev4 issues regardless of progress status.</p><p>Decision authority thresholds have been adjusted based on feedback from legal and finance: Managers may approve credits up to 5% of annual contract value or $5,000 maximum, VPs up to 15% or $25,000, and C-suite unlimited with board notification for credits exceeding $100,000. A new escalation role, Customer Advocate, has been added to own communication during complex escalations, ensuring consistent messaging and proactive status updates. The matrix now includes post-escalation requirements: root cause analysis within 5 business days, corrective action plan within 10 business days, and customer follow-up meeting to review improvements. All SLAs and thresholds have been reviewed by the legal team for consistency with customer contracts and applicable regulations.</p>', 'PENDING', 4, '2026-01-29 10:00:00'),
(55, 7, 6, 'Final customer support escalation policy', '<h1>Final Customer Support Escalation Policy - Approved</h1><p>This final escalation policy has been approved by the VP of Customer Success and legal team, effective March 1, 2026. The policy incorporates SLAs and thresholds from version 5, with one modification: executive escalation threshold changed from 4 hours to 6 hours for Sev2 issues to allow additional investigation time before executive involvement. All other triggers and SLAs remain as defined. The policy has been published in the support playbook and communicated to all customer-facing teams through mandatory training completed by February 20th.</p><p>Implementation includes automated escalation rules in Zendesk (configured February 25th), dashboard for real-time escalation monitoring, and weekly escalation review meetings to identify trends and improvement opportunities. Customer communication templates have been finalized for each escalation stage, translated into 6 languages (English, Spanish, French, German, Japanese, Portuguese). The policy will be shared with customers upon request and summarized in the customer portal. Effectiveness will be measured through reduced escalation resolution time (target 40% reduction from Q4 2025 baseline), improved customer satisfaction on escalated issues (target CSAT > 4.5/5), and reduced repeat escalations for similar issues (target < 10% within 90 days). This policy supersedes all previous escalation procedures.</p>', 'APPROVED', 5, '2026-02-01 16:00:00'),
(56, 8, 5, 'New hire training schedule', '<h1>New Hire Training Schedule - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the training schedule for new employees during their first 30 days, aligned with the onboarding checklist approved in version 4. Training is divided into three tracks: Corporate (company-wide required training), Role-Specific (functional skills), and Elective (optional enrichment). Corporate training includes compliance (harassment prevention, data privacy, security awareness), culture (company history, values, DEI), and tools (email, calendar, messaging, video conferencing). Role-specific training varies by department: Sales (CRM, sales methodology, product knowledge), Engineering (development environment, code review, deployment process), Marketing (marketing automation, analytics, brand guidelines).</p><p>The schedule allocates specific hours per track: Corporate (8 hours total, completed by day 5), Role-Specific (16 hours total, completed by day 20), Elective (4 hours total, completed by day 30). Training delivery methods include instructor-led sessions (40%), self-paced e-learning (40%), and hands-on workshops (20%). All training is tracked in the LMS, with completion required before end of probationary period (90 days). Managers receive weekly completion reports and are responsible for ensuring their new hires attend scheduled sessions. The training team will conduct monthly new hire surveys to gather feedback and continuously improve content and delivery methods.</p>', 'DRAFT', 6, '2026-01-27 08:30:00'),
(57, 8, 6, 'Training schedule with department sessions', '<h1>New Hire Training Schedule - Department Sessions Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed department-specific training sessions with dates, times, and instructors. Sales department training includes: Week 1 (CRM basics, 2 hours), Week 2 (Sales methodology - MEDDIC, 4 hours), Week 3 (Product deep dive, 6 hours), Week 4 (Competitive battle cards, 2 hours), Week 5 (Deal desk processes, 2 hours). Engineering training includes: Week 1 (Development environment setup, 4 hours), Week 2 (Code review standards, 2 hours), Week 3 (CI/CD pipeline, 4 hours), Week 4 (Testing frameworks, 4 hours), Week 5 (Security coding practices, 2 hours). Marketing training includes: Week 1 (Marketing automation - HubSpot, 4 hours), Week 2 (Analytics dashboard, 2 hours), Week 3 (Brand guidelines, 2 hours), Week 4 (Campaign management, 4 hours), Week 5 (Content strategy, 2 hours).</p><p>Cross-functional training sessions have been added for roles requiring collaboration: Sales & Marketing alignment (2 hours, week 3), Engineering & Support handoff (2 hours, week 4), and Product & Sales enablement (2 hours, week 5). All sessions are recorded and available on-demand for employees who miss live sessions due to business travel or time zone differences. The training calendar has been synchronized with the corporate events calendar to avoid conflicts with all-hands meetings, holidays, and quarterly planning offsites. Session capacity is limited to 15 participants to ensure interactivity, with multiple sessions scheduled for high-demand topics. The training team has confirmed instructor availability for all sessions through Q2 2026.</p>', 'PENDING', 7, '2026-01-30 11:00:00'),
(58, 8, 7, 'Final onboarding training plan', '<h1>Final Onboarding Training Plan - Approved</h1><p>This approved training plan incorporates department sessions from version 6 with final schedule confirmed by all department heads. Training begins on each new hire''s start date (typically Monday) with the following weekly structure: Week 1 (Corporate + Tools), Week 2 (Department Core), Week 3 (Department Advanced), Week 4 (Cross-functional + Electives). Total training hours have been balanced to 40 hours over 4 weeks, with no single week exceeding 12 hours of training to leave time for ramp-up activities and manager 1:1s.</p><p>Success metrics include completion rate (target 95% within 30 days), knowledge assessment scores (target 85% average), and new hire satisfaction (target 4.5/5 on training value survey). The training plan will be piloted with 10 new hires in March 2026, with adjustments made before full rollout in April. The LMS has been configured to automatically assign training based on job role and start date, with reminder emails sent 3 days before each session and 1 day after for any missed sessions. Managers have been trained on how to support their new hires through the training period, including protected time on calendars and regular check-ins on progress. The training budget of $50,000 for Q2 covers facilitator time, content development, and LMS licensing.</p>', 'APPROVED', 8, '2026-02-02 13:00:00'),
(59, 9, 4, 'Data retention policy draft', '<h1>Data Retention Policy - Draft</h1><p>This policy defines retention periods for different data types in compliance with legal, regulatory, and business requirements. Customer data: retained for duration of customer relationship plus 7 years for financial transactions (tax/SOX compliance), with right to deletion requests under GDPR/CCPA requiring secure deletion within 30 days of verified request. Employee data: retained for duration of employment plus 7 years post-termination for payroll records, 3 years for performance reviews, and 1 year for recruiting data (unless consent provided for longer retention). System logs: retained 1 year for security logs, 90 days for application logs, 30 days for debug logs.</p><p>Data disposition methods vary by classification: Confidential data requires cryptographic erasure or physical destruction of media, Internal data requires overwriting (3 passes minimum), Public data may be deleted via standard file system commands. Retention holds override standard schedules for data involved in legal proceedings, audits, or investigations, with holds released only upon written authorization from legal department. The policy applies to all data repositories including databases, file shares, email systems, backup tapes, and cloud storage. Exceptions require approval from the Data Governance Committee, documented with business justification and risk assessment.</p>', 'DRAFT', 9, '2026-01-28 09:00:00'),
(60, 9, 5, 'Data retention with legal review', '<h1>Data Retention Policy - Legal Review Incorporated</h1><p>This revision incorporates feedback from legal counsel on retention periods and compliance requirements. Key changes include: Customer financial data retention extended from 7 to 10 years to align with statute of limitations for fraud claims under federal law. Employee medical records (HIPAA-covered) now require 6 years post-termination instead of 3 years. Email retention reduced from 7 years to 3 years for non-business records (personal emails, newsletters, distribution lists) to reduce legal discovery costs, provided business records are properly archived to separate systems. Legal counsel also added requirements for retention of board minutes (permanent), contracts (10 years post-expiration), and intellectual property records (life of IP plus 10 years).</p><p>The policy now includes a legal hold process with specific steps: notification from legal department, preservation notice to data custodians, suspension of automated deletion, and quarterly hold status reviews. A new Data Retention Schedule (Appendix A) provides a searchable table of all data types with retention periods, legal basis, and disposition method. The legal team has approved this version pending final review by the privacy officer for GDPR consistency. A transition period of 90 days is provided for existing data to be classified and scheduled for disposition according to the new policy, with a one-time legal hold review for any data older than the new retention periods before deletion.</p>', 'PENDING', 10, '2026-01-31 10:30:00'),
(61, 9, 6, 'Final data retention policy', '<h1>Final Data Retention Policy - Approved</h1><p>This final policy incorporates legal review feedback and has been approved by the Data Governance Committee and Privacy Officer effective April 1, 2026. Retention periods are finalized as: Customer data (relationship + 10 years), Employee data (employment + 7 years), Financial records (10 years), Contracts (10 years post-expiration), System logs (1 year security, 90 days application, 30 days debug), Email (3 years for non-business records, permanent for business records archived separately). The policy includes a data classification schema (Confidential, Internal, Public) with specific handling requirements for each classification.</p><p>Implementation responsibilities: IT will configure automated retention enforcement in all systems by March 31st, including Exchange Online retention policies, SharePoint auto-delete rules, and database archival jobs. Data owners must classify their data by April 30th using the new classification tool integrated with the data catalog. The legal department will manage legal holds through a new hold management system with automated notifications and compliance reporting. Non-compliance consequences include remediation plans for first violations and escalation to executive leadership for repeated violations. The policy will be reviewed annually, with the first review scheduled for Q1 2027. All employees must acknowledge the policy through the HR portal by March 31st, with training modules available for data owners and custodians.</p>', 'APPROVED', 1, '2026-02-03 14:00:00'),
(62, 10, 5, 'Post-migration validation plan', '<h1>Post-Migration Validation Plan - Draft</h1><p>This document defines the validation process after each migration wave to confirm successful transition to AWS. Validation includes three phases: Technical validation (infrastructure health, configuration correctness, security controls), Functional validation (application behavior, data integrity, performance), and Business validation (user acceptance, SLA compliance, customer impact). Technical validation checks include EC2 instance status (all running), security group rules (no open unnecessary ports), backup configuration (automated snapshots enabled), and monitoring alarms (critical metrics configured). Functional validation includes smoke tests for each application, data comparison between source and target (checksum verification for databases), and performance benchmarking (response times within 10% of baseline).</p><p>Business validation requires sign-off from application owners, user acceptance testing by power users (minimum 5 per application), and customer impact assessment (zero unplanned downtime for customer-facing systems). Validation gates are defined for each wave: Wave 1 (non-prod) requires technical and functional validation only; Wave 2 (internal systems) requires business validation from internal users; Wave 3 (customer-facing) requires all three phases plus 72-hour stability period with automated canary testing every 15 minutes. Validation failures trigger rollback within 2 hours, with root cause analysis required before next migration attempt. The validation team includes representatives from infrastructure, applications, security, and quality assurance, with the project manager responsible for sign-off collection and documentation.</p>', 'DRAFT', 2, '2026-01-29 08:00:00'),
(63, 10, 6, 'Validation plan with testing steps', '<h1>Post-Migration Validation Plan - Testing Steps Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed testing steps for each validation phase. Technical validation steps include: Step 1 - Connectivity testing (ping, traceroute, port scans), Step 2 - DNS resolution (internal and external), Step 3 - Certificate validation (expiration dates, chain trust), Step 4 - Backup verification (snapshot creation and restore test), Step 5 - Monitoring validation (test alert generation and receipt). Functional validation steps include: Step 1 - Authentication (SAML, LDAP, local), Step 2 - CRUD operations (create, read, update, delete for each data entity), Step 3 - API endpoint testing (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE with expected responses), Step 4 - Batch job execution (scheduled jobs run successfully), Step 5 - Integration testing (end-to-end workflows crossing multiple systems).</p><p>Business validation steps include: Step 1 - UAT script execution (pre-defined test cases by application owners), Step 2 - User acceptance sign-off (email confirmation or ticket approval), Step 3 - SLA validation (response times, availability, throughput against documented SLAs), Step 4 - Customer impact survey (for customer-facing systems, survey 10% of active users), Step 5 - Executive sign-off (CIO approval for production systems). Each step includes expected results, actual results field, and evidence attachment (screenshots, logs, test reports). Automated validation scripts are provided for technical and functional steps where possible, with manual validation required for business steps. The testing environment (clone of production) is available for dry-run validation before each wave.</p>', 'PENDING', 3, '2026-02-01 11:00:00'),
(64, 10, 7, 'Final migration validation protocol', '<h1>Final Migration Validation Protocol - Approved</h1><p>This approved validation protocol incorporates testing steps from version 6 with final approval from the change advisory committee. The protocol applies to all three migration waves, with enhanced requirements for wave 3 (customer-facing systems) including additional validation: load testing at 150% peak traffic, disaster recovery failover test (to secondary region), and security penetration testing for any new attack surfaces. Validation success criteria are defined: 100% of technical validation steps passed, 100% of functional validation steps passed, 95% of business validation steps passed (with exceptions documented and risk-accepted), and zero severity 1 or 2 incidents during stability period.</p><p>The protocol includes a validation dashboard in Confluence showing real-time status of all steps, with red/yellow/green indicators and automated alerts for failures. Validation leads are assigned for each phase: Infrastructure lead for technical, Applications lead for functional, Business lead for business validation. Sign-off authority is delegated: wave 1 (non-prod) requires infrastructure lead sign-off, wave 2 (internal) requires applications lead plus business lead, wave 3 (customer-facing) requires all three leads plus CIO approval. The protocol has been tested in a pilot migration of 5 development servers with 100% success rate. All team members have completed validation training, including a simulation exercise on February 15th. This protocol is authorized for use effective immediately and will be reviewed after wave 1 to identify any improvements needed before wave 2.</p>', 'APPROVED', 4, '2026-02-04 15:30:00'),
(65, 1, 6, 'Q1 report executive summary', '<h1>Q1 Financial Report - Executive Summary Draft</h1><p>This executive summary condenses the full Q1 financial report for board and investor communications. Q1 2026 results exceeded expectations with revenue of $4.52M (7.6% above forecast) and net income of $892,000 (5.2% above forecast). Key drivers included stronger-than-expected enterprise sales ($2.1M vs $1.8M forecast) and lower operating expenses due to marketing spend delays. The balance sheet remains strong with $3.2M in cash, no debt, and accounts receivable DSO improved to 38 days from 45 days in Q4 2025. EBITDA margin of 22% meets the full-year target of 20-25%, positioning the company well for the remaining quarters.</p><p>Strategic highlights include the successful beta launch of Project Phoenix with 200 companies in early access, expansion into the Asia-Pacific market with 3 new enterprise customers, and achievement of SOC2 Type II certification strengthening security posture for enterprise deals. Risks and challenges include supply chain constraints affecting hardware delivery (15% probability of Q2 impact), increased competition from a new entrant, and sales team attrition at 12% annualized. Q2 guidance of $5.3M revenue and $1.0M net income assumes successful product launch and continued enterprise momentum. The board is requested to approve the Q1 results and Q2 guidance at the February 10th meeting.</p>', 'DRAFT', 5, '2026-01-30 09:00:00'),
(66, 1, 7, 'Executive summary with board notes', '<h1>Q1 Executive Summary - Board Notes Added</h1><p>This revision adds notes from the board finance committee for discussion at the February 10th board meeting. Specific questions raised by the committee include: explanation for the 8% under-spend in marketing (requesting detailed variance analysis), rationale for maintaining $3.2M cash reserves rather than deploying for share repurchases or acquisitions, and competitive positioning strategy following competitor launch announcement. Additional requested analysis includes customer concentration risk (top 10 customers represent 35% of revenue vs 30% industry benchmark), sales capacity analysis (current 85% utilization vs target 90-95%), and product roadmap alignment with Q2 revenue guidance.</p><p>The summary now includes a risk mitigation matrix addressing each board concern: Marketing variance explained by campaign timing shifts (Q2 spend expected to normalize), cash deployment options analysis attached as Appendix B (share buyback vs R&D investment vs M&A), and competitive response plan (discounting strategy, feature acceleration, and customer retention programs). Customer concentration risk will be reviewed quarterly with action plans to diversify if any single customer exceeds 10% of revenue. Sales capacity analysis recommends hiring 3 additional AEs in Q2 to reach target utilization. The CEO and CFO will present these responses at the board meeting, with this summary serving as pre-read materials distributed 5 days in advance.</p>', 'PENDING', 6, '2026-02-02 10:00:00'),
(67, 1, 8, 'Final Q1 executive summary', '<h1>Final Q1 Executive Summary - Approved</h1><p>This final executive summary incorporates board feedback and has been approved for distribution to shareholders and the public as part of the Q1 earnings release. Q1 results are reported as follows: Revenue $4.52M (up 15% QoQ, up 28% YoY), Net Income $892,000 (18% of cost savings from operational efficiency initiatives), Cash from Operations $1.1M (strong conversion driven by improved collections). The board approved Q2 guidance of $5.3M revenue and $1.0M net income, with the understanding that management will provide monthly updates on Project Phoenix launch performance and competitive response effectiveness.</p><p>The summary will be included in the Form 8-K filed with the SEC on February 12th, the shareholder letter mailed February 15th, and the investor presentation posted on the company website February 16th. The CEO and CFO will host an earnings call on February 16th at 8:30am ET to discuss results and answer analyst questions. Key messages for the call include confidence in Q2 guidance, excitement about Project Phoenix market reception, and commitment to maintaining strong balance sheet while exploring strategic M&A opportunities in the AI analytics space. This summary supersedes all previous versions and serves as the official communication document for Q1 2026 results.</p>', 'APPROVED', 7, '2026-02-05 13:00:00'),
(68, 2, 8, 'CRM risk assessment', '<h1>CRM Risk Assessment - Draft</h1><p>This document assesses risks associated with the CRM implementation project approved in version 7. Risk categories include Technical (integration complexity, data migration, performance), Operational (user adoption, business process changes, support readiness), Financial (budget overrun, ROI shortfall, vendor viability), and Schedule (timeline slippage, resource availability, dependency delays). Each risk is assessed for probability (Low/Medium/High) and impact (Low/Medium/High) with a combined risk score (1-9). High-priority risks (score 7-9) require mitigation plans; medium-priority (4-6) require monitoring; low-priority (1-3) are accepted.</p><p>Top risks identified: Integration complexity with ERP (Probability: High, Impact: High, Score: 9) - mitigation includes dedicated integration team, weekly vendor syncs, and extended testing phase. User adoption (High, High, 9) - mitigation includes change management plan, super-user program, and executive sponsorship. Data quality issues (Medium, High, 6) - mitigation includes data cleansing before migration, validation rules in target system, and post-go-live data stewardship. Budget overrun (Low, Medium, 3) - accepted with contingency buffer. The risk register will be reviewed weekly by the project manager and monthly by the steering committee, with risk owners assigned for each mitigation action.</p>', 'DRAFT', 8, '2026-01-31 08:30:00'),
(69, 2, 9, 'Risk assessment with mitigation plan', '<h1>CRM Risk Assessment - Mitigation Plan Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed mitigation plans for high-priority risks identified in version 8. Integration complexity mitigation includes: dedicated integration architect (FTE for 12 weeks), daily standups between CRM and ERP teams, automated integration testing suite (50+ test cases), and fallback option of batch sync if real-time integration fails (approved by architecture review board). User adoption mitigation includes: 3-phase rollout (pilot with 20 power users, wave 1 with 50 early adopters, wave 2 with remaining 150 users), adoption dashboard tracking login frequency, data completeness, and feature usage, with weekly coaching sessions for low-adoption users.</p><p>Data quality mitigation includes: pre-migration data audit (500,000 records reviewed for completeness, accuracy, consistency), automated data validation scripts comparing source and target, data quality scorecard with monthly reporting to data governance committee, and data steward assigned for each major object (accounts, contacts, opportunities, cases). Additional risks identified during mitigation planning: Vendor support responsiveness (Medium, Medium, 4) - mitigation includes 24/7 support entitlement, named support engineer, and weekly health checks. Training effectiveness (Medium, Medium, 4) - mitigation includes knowledge assessments, sandbox environment for practice, and office hours for post-training questions. The risk register now includes trigger thresholds for contingency activation (e.g., integration testing failure rate >10% triggers escalation to steering committee).</p>', 'PENDING', 9, '2026-02-03 14:00:00'),
(70, 2, 10, 'Final CRM risk register', '<h1>Final CRM Risk Register - Approved</h1><p>This approved risk register incorporates all mitigation plans from version 9 and has been reviewed by the steering committee. Risk scores have been recalculated post-mitigation: Integration complexity reduced from 9 to 4 (residual risk accepted), User adoption reduced from 9 to 5 (monitoring required), Data quality reduced from 6 to 3 (accepted). Two new risks identified post-mitigation: Post-go-live support readiness (Medium, Medium, 4) - mitigation includes extended vendor support for 30 days post-launch, internal support team training completed before go-live, and war room staffed for first week. Security compliance (Low, High, 3) - mitigation includes security review completed, penetration testing scheduled, and data classification applied.</p><p>The risk register is now a living document stored in the project SharePoint site, with weekly updates required from risk owners. Contingency budget of $23,750 (5% of project budget) is allocated for risk response, with drawdown requiring approval from project sponsor for amounts exceeding $5,000. The steering committee will review the risk register at each monthly meeting, with quarterly deep-dives on high-priority risks. All team members have acknowledged their risk management responsibilities through project onboarding. This risk register is authorized for use and will be audited by the PMO at project milestones (end of each phase) to ensure compliance with risk management processes defined in the project management plan.</p>', 'APPROVED', 10, '2026-02-06 11:00:00'),
(71, 3, 7, 'Benefits update for remote employees', '<h1>Remote Employee Benefits Update - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines benefits changes for remote employees effective April 1, 2026, following the remote work policy approved in version 6. New benefits include: Home office stipend ($500 one-time for furniture/equipment), Internet reimbursement ($50 monthly), Wellness stipend ($300 quarterly for gym, mental health apps, ergonomic assessments), and Learning & Development budget ($1,000 annually for remote-eligible courses/certifications). These benefits are available only to employees classified as Remote-First (4+ days remote per week) and are pro-rated for part-time employees based on scheduled hours. Hybrid employees (2-3 office days) remain eligible for standard benefits (commuter benefits, office perks) but not remote-specific offerings.</p><p>Implementation details: Home office stipend claims require itemized receipts submitted through the expense system with manager approval, paid within 30 days of approval. Internet reimbursement requires proof of service (billing statement) and is paid as taxable benefit (IRS guidance). Wellness stipend is administered through a benefits card (Flexible Spending) that can be used at approved vendors (gym memberships, ClassPass, Headspace, Calm, ergonomic assessment services). L&D budget can be used for online courses (Coursera, Udemy, LinkedIn Learning), certification exams (PMP, AWS, Salesforce), and virtual conference attendance. The benefits package is designed to be cost-neutral to the company (total budget $150,000 annually) by reducing office-related expenses (real estate, utilities, snacks, commuting subsidies) for remote employees.</p>', 'DRAFT', 1, '2026-02-01 09:00:00'),
(72, 3, 8, 'Benefits package revised', '<h1>Remote Employee Benefits - Revised Package</h1><p>This revision adjusts benefits based on employee feedback and budget analysis. The home office stipend increased from $500 to $750 following survey feedback that 68% of remote employees spent >$500 on initial setup. Internet reimbursement decreased from $50 to $40 monthly due to lower-than-expected claims in pilot program (average claim $38). Wellness stipend restructured from $300 quarterly to $1,000 annually (same total) to simplify administration and allow larger purchases (e.g., treadmill desk, standing desk converter). L&D budget increased from $1,000 to $1,500 annually based on competitive benchmarking against industry peers (75th percentile for tech companies of similar size).</p><p>New benefits added: Virtual mental health services (8 free therapy sessions annually through BetterHelp, $500 value), Home internet security stipend ($100 annually for VPN subscription or router upgrade), and Coworking space credits (5 days per quarter at WeWork or similar, $400 value). Total benefit value increased from $2,600 to $3,650 annually per remote employee, increasing total program budget from $150,000 to $210,000 for 60 remote employees. The CFO has requested justification for the budget increase, which HR has provided through ROI analysis (estimated 5% reduction in remote employee turnover from 15% to 10%, saving $300,000 in recruiting costs annually). The revised package requires approval from the compensation committee before implementation.</p>', 'PENDING', 2, '2026-02-04 10:30:00'),
(73, 3, 9, 'Final remote benefits policy', '<h1>Final Remote Benefits Policy - Approved</h1><p>This approved policy incorporates the revised benefits package from version 8 with final budget approval from the compensation committee. Total benefit value is set at $3,500 annually per remote employee (rounded down from $3,650 for budget predictability) with the following components: Home office stipend $750 (one-time), Internet reimbursement $40 monthly ($480 annual), Wellness stipend $1,000 annual, L&D budget $1,500 annual, Virtual mental health (8 sessions, $500 value), Home security $100 annual, Coworking credits (5 days quarterly, $400 value). The policy applies to all employees classified as Remote-First (4+ days remote per week) as of April 1, 2026, with pro-ration for part-time and mid-year classification changes.</p><p>Implementation timeline: Benefits portal updated by March 15th, employee communications sent March 20th, claims processing available April 1st. The HR team will host two virtual town halls (March 22nd and March 25th) to explain the policy and answer questions. A transition period of 60 days is provided for existing remote employees to submit home office stipend claims retroactive to April 1st. The policy will be reviewed after 6 months (October 1, 2026) to assess utilization, employee satisfaction, and ROI on turnover reduction. The total program budget of $210,000 has been allocated from the corporate benefits pool, with quarterly reporting to the CFO on spend vs budget. This policy supersedes all previous remote benefits communications and is effective immediately upon approval.</p>', 'APPROVED', 3, '2026-02-07 16:00:00'),
(74, 4, 8, 'Post-launch survey design', '<h1>Post-Launch Survey Design - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the survey design for gathering feedback from Project Phoenix launch attendees and early adopters. Two survey versions are planned: Post-event survey (for launch attendees) and Post-trial survey (for customers who complete 30-day free trial). Post-event survey includes 10 questions covering: Content relevance (scale 1-5), Speaker effectiveness (scale 1-5), Likelihood to recommend (NPS 0-10), Purchase intent (scale 1-5), Product feature interest (select all that apply), Preferred next steps (demo, trial, contact sales, none), Open-ended feedback (strengths, improvements, additional topics). The survey is designed to take 3-5 minutes to complete, with a target completion rate of 20% (industry benchmark for event surveys).</p><p>Post-trial survey includes 15 questions covering: Onboarding experience (scale 1-5), Feature usage (which features used, frequency), Value realization (scale 1-5), Ease of use (System Usability Scale - 10 questions), Likelihood to purchase (scale 1-5), Purchase timeframe (immediate, 1-3 months, 3-6 months, 6+ months, never), Price perception (too high, about right, too low), Open-ended feedback (what worked well, what could be improved, why purchasing or not). The survey is triggered automatically 30 days after trial start, with reminder emails at day 28, 32, and 35 if not completed. Target completion rate is 30% based on industry benchmarks for post-trial surveys. Survey data will be analyzed in Tableau with dashboards shared with product, sales, and marketing teams weekly during launch quarter.</p>', 'DRAFT', 4, '2026-02-02 08:00:00'),
(75, 4, 9, 'Survey with customer feedback metrics', '<h1>Post-Launch Survey - Feedback Metrics Added</h1><p>This revision adds specific feedback metrics and analytical frameworks to the survey design. Key metrics include: Net Promoter Score (NPS) calculated from likelihood to recommend (9-10 Promoters, 7-8 Passives, 0-6 Detractors) with target NPS of +40 (industry average for B2B software launches). Customer Satisfaction Score (CSAT) from content relevance and speaker effectiveness questions, target 4.2/5. Purchase intent score, target 3.5/5. System Usability Scale (SUS) score, target 70 (above average, 68 is industry benchmark). Feature adoption rate, target >50% of features used by majority of respondents. Each metric includes segmentation by customer type (new vs existing), company size (enterprise vs mid-market vs SMB), and region (NA vs EMEA vs APAC).</p><p>The survey now includes branching logic to reduce respondent fatigue: Post-event survey branches based on purchase intent (high intent respondents see demo scheduling question, low intent see feedback on barriers). Post-trial survey branches based on feature usage (high usage see advanced feature questions, low usage see onboarding feedback). Open-ended responses will be analyzed using natural language processing (MonkeyLearn) to identify themes and sentiment, with weekly reports to product management. A feedback loop is established: survey insights will be reviewed in weekly product team meetings, with action items assigned and tracked in Jira. The survey instrument has been reviewed by legal for compliance with anti-bribery laws (no incentives offered for feedback) and data privacy regulations (anonymous responses, no PII collected unless voluntarily provided).</p>', 'PENDING', 5, '2026-02-05 11:00:00'),
(76, 4, 10, 'Final post-launch feedback plan', '<h1>Final Post-Launch Feedback Plan - Approved</h1><p>This approved plan incorporates feedback metrics from version 9 with final sign-off from product, marketing, and legal teams. Surveys will launch on April 16th (post-event) and May 15th (post-trial for first cohort of trial users). Survey platforms selected: Typeform for post-event (better branding customization) and SurveyMonkey for post-trial (native integration with CRM for tracking). Survey invitations will be sent via email from the product marketing manager, with a personalized subject line including the recipient''s name and company to improve open rates (target 40% open rate, 20% completion rate for post-event; 50% open rate, 30% completion rate for post-trial).</p><p>Data analysis and reporting: Weekly automated reports to product, sales, and marketing leadership every Monday morning. Monthly deep-dive reviews on the last Thursday of each month with cross-functional team (product management, product marketing, sales operations, customer success). A feedback repository will be maintained in Airtable, tagging each piece of feedback by source (survey, support ticket, sales call, social media), sentiment (positive, neutral, negative), and theme (pricing, features, usability, documentation, support). The repository will inform product roadmap prioritization (weighted scoring based on frequency and customer value) and sales enablement content (objection handling, competitive battle cards). The feedback plan has a budget of $15,000 for survey tool licensing, NLP analysis, and dashboard development, approved by the CMO. This plan is authorized for execution effective immediately.</p>', 'APPROVED', 6, '2026-02-08 13:30:00'),
(77, 5, 7, 'Security awareness training content', '<h1>Security Awareness Training Content - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines the content for mandatory security awareness training for all employees, required annually as part of the security roadmap approved in version 6. Training modules include: Module 1 - Phishing attacks (how to identify, what to do, reporting procedures), Module 2 - Password security (password managers, MFA, avoiding reuse), Module 3 - Data protection (classification, handling, encryption, sharing), Module 4 - Physical security (clean desk policy, badge usage, visitor management), Module 5 - Social engineering (vishing, tailgating, pretexting), Module 6 - Incident response (how to report, what to expect, do''s and don''ts). Each module includes a 5-10 minute video, knowledge check questions (3-5 per module), and real-world examples relevant to our industry.</p><p>Training delivery: Hosted in the LMS (Workday Learning), assigned to all employees on March 1st with 60 days to complete. Automated reminders at day 30, 45, 55 if not completed. Non-completion consequences include restricted system access (day 61), manager notification (day 45), and escalation to HR for repeated non-compliance (day 90). Completion tracking dashboard available to managers and security team. The training content was developed by the security team in partnership with an external vendor (KnowBe4) with annual updates required. A phishing simulation program will complement the training, with simulated phishing emails sent quarterly to all employees, and remedial training assigned to those who fail (click on link or enter credentials). The security team will report training completion rates and phishing simulation results to the board audit committee quarterly.</p>', 'DRAFT', 7, '2026-02-03 09:00:00'),
(78, 5, 8, 'Training modules for all staff', '<h1>Security Awareness Training - All Staff Modules</h1><p>This revision adds role-specific modules to the training program, recognizing that different roles face different security risks. Executive modules (C-suite, VPs, directors) add: Targeted phishing (spear phishing, whaling), Travel security (VPN, device protection, physical security in hotels), Social media risks (OSINT, impersonation), and Regulatory reporting obligations (SEC breach disclosure, GDPR breach notification). Finance team modules add: Wire transfer fraud (CEO impersonation, vendor invoice fraud), Financial statement integrity (access controls, segregation of duties), and Payment processing security (PCI compliance, tokenization). Engineering modules add: Secure coding practices (OWASP Top 10, input validation, output encoding), Dependency management (vulnerable libraries, software composition analysis), and Secrets management (API keys, credentials in code). HR modules add: Employee data privacy (PII handling, access controls), Background check procedures, and Insider threat awareness (behavioral indicators, reporting).</p><p>Sales and customer support modules add: Customer data handling (access controls, sharing limitations), Social engineering defenses (vishing attempts impersonating customers), and CRM security best practices (session timeouts, audit logging). All employees complete the 6 core modules (60 minutes total), plus 2-3 role-specific modules (20-30 minutes additional) for a total of 80-90 minutes annually. Role-specific modules are assigned automatically based on job code in HRIS, with quarterly reviews to ensure accuracy as roles change. The training content has been localized into 6 languages (English, Spanish, French, German, Japanese, Portuguese) for global employees. A pilot of the training program with 50 employees from various roles will run February 15-29th, with feedback collected to refine content before full rollout on March 1st.</p>', 'PENDING', 8, '2026-02-06 10:00:00'),
(79, 5, 9, 'Final security training program', '<h1>Final Security Training Program - Approved</h1><p>This approved training program incorporates role-specific modules from version 8 with final content reviewed by legal and HR. Total training time is confirmed at 75 minutes for most employees (core modules 55 minutes + role-specific 20 minutes), with executives at 90 minutes (additional executive module 15 minutes). The training is mandatory for all employees, contractors, and temporary workers with system access, due by April 30, 2026 (60 days from March 1st assignment). The pilot program with 50 employees achieved 100% completion, 92% knowledge assessment pass rate (target 85%), and 4.6/5 satisfaction rating (target 4.5). Feedback incorporated includes shorter videos (reduced from 10 to 7 minutes average), more interactive elements (drag-and-drop, scenario-based questions), and mobile-friendly format (responsive design for smartphone completion).</p><p>Phishing simulation program details: Quarterly simulations (March, June, September, December) using a mix of templates (delivery notification, password reset, document share, social media alert). Baseline click rate from December 2025 was 18% (industry average 20%), with target reduction to 10% by December 2026. Employees who click on simulated phishing links receive immediate remedial training (5-minute module) and are flagged for manager awareness. Repeat offenders (3+ clicks in 12 months) receive one-on-one coaching with security team and mandatory monthly reminders. The training program has a budget of $45,000 for KnowBe4 licensing ($25,000 annually), content localization ($10,000 one-time), and LMS integration ($10,000 one-time). The CISO will present training completion and phishing simulation results to the board audit committee quarterly, with the first report due May 15th. This program is authorized for implementation effective March 1, 2026.</p>', 'APPROVED', 9, '2026-02-09 14:00:00'),
(80, 6, 8, 'Sales performance metrics dashboard', '<h1>Sales Performance Metrics Dashboard - Draft</h1><p>This document defines the sales performance metrics dashboard to be built in Salesforce CRM and Tableau for Q2 2026. The dashboard includes four sections: Pipeline Health (total pipeline value, weighted pipeline, coverage ratio, aging, win rate by stage), Sales Activity (calls, emails, demos, meetings per rep, conversion rates), Team Performance (attainment vs quota, rank by rep and region, trend vs prior quarter), and Forecast Accuracy (commit vs forecast, slippage rate, bias analysis). Metrics are refreshed daily with data from Salesforce activities, call logs, email engagement (Outreach.io integration), and meeting data (Zoom integration).</p><p>Targets for each metric: Pipeline coverage 3x quota (target 3.0x, current 2.5x), Win rate 25% (target 25%, current 22%), Average deal size $25,000 (target $25,000, current $22,000), Sales cycle 60 days (target 60 days, current 68 days), Activity metrics: 50 calls/week (target 50, current 42), 20 emails/week (target 20, current 18), 5 demos/week (target 5, current 4). The dashboard will be used in weekly sales team meetings (Mondays 10am) and monthly QBRs. Access is available to all sales reps (their own metrics only), managers (team metrics), and executives (all metrics). The dashboard development requires 80 hours of Salesforce admin time and 40 hours of Tableau developer time, budgeted at $18,000 from the sales operations budget.</p>', 'DRAFT', 10, '2026-02-04 08:30:00'),
(81, 6, 9, 'Dashboard with real-time KPIs', '<h1>Sales Dashboard - Real-Time KPIs Added</h1><p>This revision adds real-time key performance indicators to the dashboard, enabling immediate visibility into sales execution. Real-time KPIs include: Live deal board (opportunities updated in last hour, changes by rep), Activity feed (recent calls, emails, meetings with timestamps), Leaderboard (today''s top performers by meetings booked, demos completed), and Alerting (deals at risk, stalled opportunities, overdue tasks). These KPIs are updated every 15 minutes from Salesforce streaming APIs, with a maximum latency of 30 seconds for activity feed. The real-time view is designed for sales managers to monitor team activity throughout the day without waiting for daily reports.</p><p>Technical implementation: Salesforce Platform Events for opportunity changes, Kafka for activity stream processing, WebSockets for pushing updates to Tableau dashboards (Tableau Pulse). Infrastructure requirements include 2 additional EC2 instances for stream processing ($200/month) and increased Tableau licensing for real-time data sources ($500/month). The sales operations team has tested the real-time architecture with 50 concurrent users achieving sub-1 second latency. Security controls include row-level security (reps see only their own data), session timeouts (30 minutes of inactivity), and audit logging of all dashboard access. The real-time dashboard will be piloted with 10 sales managers in February, with full rollout planned for March 1st if pilot successful. The additional $8,400 annual infrastructure cost has been approved by the VP of Sales as an investment in sales productivity.</p>', 'PENDING', 1, '2026-02-07 13:00:00'),
(82, 6, 10, 'Final sales dashboard Q2', '<h1>Final Sales Dashboard - Q2 2026</h1><p>This approved dashboard incorporates real-time KPIs from version 9 with final sign-off from sales leadership and IT. The dashboard will be deployed in production on March 1, 2026, with training provided to all sales reps and managers during the last week of February. Key features include: Personalized home page for each user (rep view, manager view, executive view), Mobile app (iOS and Android) for access on the go, Scheduled reports (daily summary emails at 8am, weekly team reports on Friday), and Export capabilities (CSV, PDF, PowerPoint). The dashboard has been tested with 100 concurrent users achieving 2 second average load time (target <3 seconds).</p><p>Success metrics for dashboard adoption: 90% of sales reps using dashboard weekly (measured by login frequency), 80% of managers using real-time view daily, and 50% reduction in manual report requests to sales operations (baseline 20 requests per week). The sales operations team will provide office hours (Mondays and Wednesdays, 2-3pm) for the first month to answer questions and gather feedback. A feedback loop is established: feature requests logged in Jira, prioritized monthly based on votes from sales team, and released in bi-weekly sprints. The dashboard is a living tool, with quarterly reviews scheduled to add/remove metrics based on evolving business needs. This dashboard supersedes all previous sales reporting tools and becomes the single source of truth for sales performance metrics effective March 1, 2026.</p>', 'APPROVED', 2, '2026-02-10 11:00:00'),
(83, 7, 7, 'Customer satisfaction survey template', '<h1>Customer Satisfaction Survey Template - Draft</h1><p>This document provides a standardized survey template for measuring customer satisfaction across all touchpoints. The template includes three survey types: Transactional (sent after support ticket closure, sales interaction, or professional services engagement), Relationship (sent quarterly to account owners), and Renewal (sent 90 days before contract expiration). Transactional survey includes 5 questions: CSAT for interaction (scale 1-5), NPS for likelihood to recommend (0-10), Effort score (how easy was it to resolve your issue, scale 1-5), Open-ended feedback (what went well, what could be improved), and Follow-up permission (checkbox for sales/support to contact).</p><p>Relationship survey includes 12 questions covering: Overall satisfaction (CSAT), Likelihood to recommend (NPS), Product satisfaction (features, reliability, performance), Support satisfaction (responsiveness, expertise, resolution time), Value satisfaction (ROI, competitive positioning), and Open-ended (strengths, areas for improvement, product roadmap requests). Renewal survey includes 20 questions covering all relationship topics plus: Renewal intent (scale 1-5), Contract value expectations (increase, same, decrease), Competitive threats (considering alternatives, which vendors), and Reference willingness (willing to be a reference, case study, testimonial). All surveys include branding (company logo, colors), mobile-responsive design, and estimated completion time displayed (2 minutes for transactional, 5 minutes for relationship, 8 minutes for renewal).</p>', 'DRAFT', 3, '2026-02-05 09:00:00'),
(84, 7, 8, 'Survey with NPS and CSAT questions', '<h1>Customer Satisfaction Survey - NPS and CSAT Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed NPS and CSAT methodologies to the survey template. NPS question wording standardized to \"How likely are you to recommend [Company Name] to a colleague or friend?\" with 0-10 scale. Follow-up question for Promoters (9-10): \"What is the primary reason for your loyalty?\" (open-ended). For Passives (7-8): \"What would need to improve for you to become a promoter?\" (open-ended). For Detractors (0-6): \"What is the primary reason for your dissatisfaction?\" (open-ended with category selection: product, support, price, competition, other). NPS is calculated as % Promoters minus % Detractors, reported monthly with trend lines and segmentation by customer tier, region, and product line.</p><p>CSAT question wording: \"Overall, how satisfied were you with your recent experience with [support/sales/ services]?\" with 5-point scale (Very Dissatisfied to Very Satisfied). CSAT score is % of responses 4 or 5 (Satisfied or Very Satisfied). The survey includes a Customer Effort Score (CES) question: \"How much effort did you personally have to put forth to handle your request?\" with 5-point scale (Very Low Effort to Very High Effort), with target of 80% responses in Very Low or Low Effort categories. Open-ended responses are analyzed using sentiment analysis (positive, neutral, negative) and topic modeling to identify common themes. Survey data is integrated with customer CRM record, enabling 360-degree view of customer health. A closed-loop process is defined: Detractors and low-effort scores trigger automatic alert to customer success manager within 1 hour, with required follow-up within 24 hours to address concerns.</p>', 'PENDING', 4, '2026-02-08 10:30:00'),
(85, 7, 9, 'Final customer feedback survey', '<h1>Final Customer Feedback Survey - Approved</h1><p>This approved survey template incorporates NPS and CSAT methodologies from version 8 with final approval from customer success, product, and legal teams. The survey will be deployed via email using the customer success platform (Gainsight) with automated triggers based on customer events. Transactional surveys triggered within 1 hour of ticket closure or sales interaction completion. Relationship surveys triggered quarterly on the first day of the month following each quarter (April 1, July 1, October 1, January 1). Renewal surveys triggered 90 days before contract expiration date. Survey fatigue rules prevent customers from receiving more than 1 transactional survey per week and more than 1 relationship survey per quarter.</p><p>Target response rates: Transactional 25%, Relationship 20%, Renewal 40%. Incentives offered for survey completion: $5 Amazon gift card for transactional (up to 500 per quarter), $25 donation to charity of choice for relationship (up to 200 per quarter), $50 account credit for renewal (applied to next invoice). Legal has approved incentives as compliant with anti-bribery laws (nominal value, not contingent on positive responses). Survey data will be analyzed in Tableau with dashboards shared weekly with customer success leadership and monthly with executive team. A quarterly customer feedback review will be conducted with product, support, sales, and success teams to identify improvement opportunities and track progress against action plans. This survey program supersedes all previous feedback collection methods and becomes the official Voice of Customer program effective April 1, 2026.</p>', 'APPROVED', 5, '2026-02-11 15:00:00'),
(86, 8, 8, 'Mentorship program guidelines', '<h1>Mentorship Program Guidelines - Draft</h1><p>This document establishes guidelines for the company mentorship program launching in Q2 2026. The program pairs junior employees (mentees) with senior employees (mentors) for 6-month relationships focused on career development. Eligibility: Mentees are employees in individual contributor roles with less than 2 years at the company or less than 5 years total experience. Mentors are senior individual contributors or managers with at least 5 years experience and demonstrated leadership behaviors. Participation is voluntary for both parties, with mentor applications reviewed by HR and mentee applications accepted on a rolling basis. Program capacity is 50 pairs per cohort, with cohorts starting April 1st and October 1st annually.</p><p>Expectations: Minimum 1-hour meeting monthly (in-person or virtual), goal setting at program start (3-5 development goals), progress check-ins at month 3, and final review at month 6. Topics may include skill development, career planning, organizational navigation, work-life balance, and leadership preparation. Confidentiality is required for all mentor-mentee discussions, with exceptions only for imminent harm or legal/ethical violations. HR provides training for all mentors (2-hour session) and mentees (1-hour session) covering roles, expectations, communication skills, and goal setting. Program success metrics include mentor/mentee satisfaction (target 4.5/5), goal completion rate (target 80%), and mentee retention/promotion rates (target 10% higher than non-participants).</p>', 'DRAFT', 6, '2026-02-06 08:00:00'),
(87, 8, 9, 'Mentorship program with pairings', '<h1>Mentorship Program - Pairings Added</h1><p>This revision adds the pairing process and matching criteria to the mentorship guidelines. Pairings are facilitated by HR using a matching algorithm based on: Career interests (mentee selected from list of 12 development areas), Functional alignment (same or adjacent department preferred), Diversity considerations (cross-functional, cross-generational, cross-cultural to maximize learning), and Availability (time zone overlap, meeting preference). The algorithm produces 3 potential matches per mentee, with final selection by mentee after reviewing mentor profiles (bio, experience, expertise, mentoring philosophy). Mentors review and accept matches within 5 business days; declined matches return to pool for reassignment.</p><p>The pilot cohort (April 1 - September 30, 2026) will include 25 pairs selected from 100 applications (50 mentors, 50 mentees) using a lottery system if oversubscribed. Priority given to first-time mentees and mentors with relevant expertise. Pairings announced March 15th, with kickoff event March 25th (virtual, 2 hours) covering program overview, goal-setting workshop, and first meeting scheduling. Mid-program check-in (July 15th) includes survey and optional group coaching session. End-of-program celebration (October 5th) recognizes completions and shares success stories. Program evaluation includes pre- and post-program surveys measuring mentee confidence (1-5 scale) in career development areas, mentor satisfaction with the experience, and ROI calculation based on mentee retention and promotion rates compared to control group (non-participants with similar demographics).</p>', 'PENDING', 7, '2026-02-09 11:00:00'),
(88, 8, 10, 'Final mentorship program handbook', '<h1>Final Mentorship Program Handbook - Approved</h1><p>This approved handbook incorporates the pairing process from version 9 with final approval from HR leadership and legal. The program launches April 1, 2026, with applications open February 15 - March 10. The handbook includes detailed sections: Program overview and philosophy, Roles and responsibilities (mentor, mentee, HR program manager), Matching process and timeline, Meeting guidelines (agenda templates, discussion topics, resources), Confidentiality agreement, Code of conduct, Conflict resolution process, and Program evaluation methodology. All participants must acknowledge the handbook and sign participation agreements before starting the program.</p><p>Implementation details: HR program manager (dedicated 0.5 FTE) oversees matching, training, check-ins, and evaluation. Mentor training sessions: March 15th (9am-11am) and March 17th (1pm-3pm) - virtual, recorded. Mentee training: March 18th (10am-11am) and March 20th (2pm-3pm) - virtual, recorded. Kickoff event: March 25th (10am-12pm) - virtual with breakout rooms for first meetings. Mid-program survey: July 1-15. End-of-program survey: September 15-30. Program budget: $25,000 for HR program manager time, training materials, kickoff event (speaker, platform), and recognition (certificates, small gifts). Success will be measured by retention (target 95% of pairs complete 6 months), satisfaction (target 4.5/5 from both mentors and mentees), and promotion rate (target 15% of mentees promoted within 12 months of program completion vs 10% baseline). This program is authorized for implementation and will be reviewed annually for continuation based on ROI analysis.</p>', 'APPROVED', 8, '2026-02-12 14:00:00'),
(89, 9, 7, 'Vendor security assessment', '<h1>Vendor Security Assessment - Draft</h1><p>This document defines the vendor security assessment process for all third-party vendors with access to company data or systems. The process applies to: Tier 1 vendors (access to sensitive data - PII, financial, intellectual property) requiring full assessment annually, Tier 2 vendors (access to internal data but not sensitive) requiring light assessment annually, and Tier 3 vendors (no data access, standard SaaS) requiring self-certification only. Assessment components include: Security questionnaire (50 questions for Tier 1, 20 for Tier 2, 5 for Tier 3), Evidence review (SOC2, ISO 27001, penetration testing results), Technical validation (vulnerability scan for Tier 1 vendors with network access), and Contract review (data protection addendum, breach notification, subcontractor management).</p><p>Assessment workflow: Vendor identified by procurement or business owner -> Risk classification (Tier 1/2/3) -> Assessment assigned to security team -> Vendor completes questionnaire and provides evidence -> Security team reviews and scores -> Remediation plan for gaps (critical gaps must be fixed before contract signing, high gaps within 30 days, medium within 90 days, low accepted) -> Final approval by CISO for Tier 1, security manager for Tier 2, business owner for Tier 3 -> Contract execution -> Ongoing monitoring (annual reassessment for Tier 1/2, continuous monitoring through security tools for network-connected vendors). The process is managed in the vendor risk management platform (Whistic) with automated reminders and reporting. The security team has 10 business days to complete each assessment from receipt of completed questionnaire.</p>', 'DRAFT', 9, '2026-02-07 09:30:00'),
(90, 9, 8, 'Vendor assessment with compliance scores', '<h1>Vendor Security Assessment - Compliance Scores Added</h1><p>This revision adds a compliance scoring methodology to the vendor assessment process. Each vendor receives a compliance score from 0-100 based on: Security questionnaire responses (40% weight), Evidence completeness and quality (30% weight), Technical validation results (20% weight), and Contract terms (10% weight). Scoring tiers: 90-100 (Low Risk) - auto-approved, 70-89 (Medium Risk) - approved with conditions (remediation plan required), 50-69 (High Risk) - approved only with executive waiver and enhanced monitoring, 0-49 (Critical Risk) - rejected, no contract allowed. The scoring model includes 20 mandatory questions (fail any results in automatic Critical Risk) covering encryption, access controls, incident response, and subcontractor management.</p><p>Compliance scores are tracked in a vendor risk dashboard with color-coded status (green/yellow/red) and trend lines. Vendors with scores below 70 trigger a remediation plan with 30-day milestones; failure to meet milestones results in score downgrade and potential contract termination. The security team conducts quarterly score reviews for all Tier 1 vendors and annual reviews for Tier 2. A vendor risk committee (security, legal, procurement) meets monthly to review high-risk vendors, exception requests, and remediation progress. The scoring methodology was benchmarked against industry standards (Shared Assessments, SIG, CAIQ) and aligns with our compliance requirements (SOC2, ISO 27001, GDPR). Legal has reviewed the scoring process for consistency with vendor contracts, noting that score-based termination requires 30-day cure period as defined in standard data processing addendum.</p>', 'PENDING', 10, '2026-02-10 10:00:00'),
(91, 9, 9, 'Final vendor security framework', '<h1>Final Vendor Security Framework - Approved</h1><p>This approved framework incorporates compliance scoring from version 8 with final sign-off from security, legal, procurement, and IT leadership. The framework becomes effective April 1, 2026, with a 90-day transition period for existing vendors to complete assessment. New vendors will be assessed before contract signing, with procurement instructed not to execute contracts without security approval (except for low-value, Tier 3 vendors approved by business owner). The framework applies to all vendors, including cloud services, professional services, hardware suppliers, and contractors, with exceptions only for vendors with no electronic access to company systems or data (approved by legal).</p><p>Implementation resources: The security team has hired a Vendor Risk Manager (start date March 15th) to oversee the program. The Whistic platform has been configured with the scoring model, automated workflows, and dashboard reporting. Training for business owners (100+ employees) will be provided through e-learning modules (15 minutes) covering vendor classification, assessment initiation, and remediation oversight. The first vendor risk committee meeting is scheduled for April 15th to review the initial queue of 50 Tier 1 vendors. Success metrics include 100% of Tier 1 vendors assessed within 90 days of framework effective date, 90% of new vendors assessed before contract signing, and 50% reduction in security incidents originating from vendor compromise (baseline 4 incidents in 2025). The framework will be audited annually by external assessors as part of SOC2 certification. This framework supersedes all previous vendor security processes.</p>', 'APPROVED', 1, '2026-02-13 13:00:00'),
(92, 10, 8, 'Cloud cost optimization plan', '<h1>Cloud Cost Optimization Plan - Draft</h1><p>This document outlines strategies to optimize AWS cloud costs following the server migration approved in version 7. Current projected monthly spend is $45,000, with target reduction of 20% ($9,000) within 90 days post-migration. Optimization strategies include: Reserved Instance (RI) purchasing (convert 60% of EC2 from On-Demand to 1-year RIs, saving $4,000/month), Right-sizing (analyze utilization and downsize over-provisioned instances, saving $2,000/month), Spot instances (move batch processing and dev environments to Spot, saving $1,500/month), Storage optimization (transition infrequently accessed data to S3-IA/Glacier, delete stale snapshots, saving $1,000/month), and Idle resource elimination (automated cleanup of unused volumes, IP addresses, load balancers, saving $500/month).</p><p>Implementation timeline: Week 1-2 (analysis and planning), Week 3-4 (RI purchase and right-sizing), Week 5-6 (Spot configuration), Week 7-8 (storage optimization), Week 9-10 (idle resource cleanup), Week 11-12 (validation and monitoring). Tools include AWS Cost Explorer, Trusted Advisor, and third-party tool (CloudCheckr) for recommendations and automation. The cloud center of excellence (CCoE) will own optimization, with weekly cost review meetings and a monthly optimization report to the CIO. Governance includes tagging strategy (cost center, environment, application, owner) enforced through AWS Organizations, budget alerts at 80%, 90%, and 100% of monthly budget, and automated shutdown of non-production resources outside business hours. The plan assumes no significant changes to workload patterns post-migration, with a 10% buffer for unexpected cost increases.</p>', 'DRAFT', 2, '2026-02-08 08:00:00'),
(93, 10, 9, 'Cost optimization with reserved instances', '<h1>Cloud Cost Optimization - Reserved Instances Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed Reserved Instance (RI) purchasing strategy to the optimization plan. RI analysis identifies 80 EC2 instances eligible for reservation (60% of total EC2 spend) with recommended purchases: 50 Standard RIs (1-year, partial upfront) for predictable production workloads, 20 Convertible RIs (1-year, no upfront) for workloads that may change instance families, and 10 Regional RIs (for flexibility across availability zones). RI purchase cost: $25,000 upfront for partial upfront RIs, plus $3,200 monthly recurring for the remaining RIs, saving $4,500/month (higher than original $4,000 estimate due to better coverage). RI utilization will be monitored monthly, with sell-back on the AWS RI Marketplace for underutilized RIs (estimated 5% waste allowed).</p><p>Additional optimization identified: Savings Plans for compute (commit $10,000/hour for 1-year, covering Fargate, Lambda, and additional EC2 beyond RIs, saving $1,000/month). Compute savings plan analysis shows 95% coverage of eligible spend at 30% discount vs On-Demand. Right-sizing recommendations now include 30 instances (15 over-provisioned, 10 under-provisioned, 5 right-sized), with projected savings of $2,500/month (up from $2,000). Spot instance strategy refined: 50% of batch jobs suitable for Spot (up from 30%), with fallback to On-Demand if Spot capacity unavailable, saving $2,000/month (up from $1,500). Total projected savings now $10,000/month (22% reduction), exceeding original target by $1,000. Implementation timeline extended to 14 weeks to accommodate RI purchase approval process (requires CFO sign-off for upfront commitment).</p>', 'PENDING', 3, '2026-02-11 14:30:00'),
(94, 10, 10, 'Final cloud cost reduction strategy', '<h1>Final Cloud Cost Reduction Strategy - Approved</h1><p>This approved strategy incorporates RI and savings plan details from version 9 with final sign-off from the CIO and CFO. Total projected savings of $9,500/month (21% reduction from $45,000 to $35,500) is approved, slightly lower than version 9 due to CFO request to reduce upfront RI commitment from $25,000 to $15,000 (purchasing 30 RIs instead of 50, saving $3,500/month instead of $4,500). The remaining $1,000/month savings gap will be achieved through additional right-sizing ($500/month) and idle resource cleanup ($500/month). Savings plan commitment set at $8,000/hour (reduced from $10,000/hour) due to conservative workload projections, saving $800/month instead of $1,000.</p><p>Implementation responsibilities: Cloud architect (RI and savings plan purchase), DevOps team (right-sizing and Spot configuration), Cloud engineer (storage optimization and idle cleanup), Finance team (budget tracking and RI amortization). The CCoE will meet weekly for the first month, then bi-weekly, with a monthly cost optimization report to the CIO including actual vs projected savings, optimization coverage, and waste metrics (unused resources, underutilized RIs). Success metrics: Achieve $9,500 monthly savings by June 30, 2026, maintain optimization coverage >80% of eligible spend, and keep waste below 5% of total cloud spend. The strategy includes a feedback loop: monthly optimization recommendations from AWS Trusted Advisor and CloudCheckr will be reviewed and implemented within 30 days. This strategy is authorized for implementation effective immediately, with first RI purchase scheduled for March 1st.</p>', 'APPROVED', 4, '2026-02-14 11:00:00'),
(95, 5, 10, 'Security incident response playbook', '<h1>Security Incident Response Playbook - Draft</h1><p>This playbook defines procedures for responding to security incidents, aligned with the security roadmap approved in version 9. Incident severity levels: Sev1 (data breach, ransomware, critical system compromise) - response within 15 minutes, CISO notification immediately; Sev2 (malware outbreak, privilege escalation, DDoS) - response within 1 hour, security manager notification; Sev3 (suspicious activity, policy violation, attempted breach) - response within 4 hours, security lead notification; Sev4 (low-risk events, false positives) - response within 24 hours, tracked for trend analysis. The playbook covers incident types: Malware/ransomware, Data breach (PII, financial, IP), Denial of service, Unauthorized access, Insider threat, Lost/stolen devices, and Third-party compromise.</p><p>Response phases: Preparation (training, tools, playbook maintenance), Detection (monitoring, alerts, user reporting), Analysis (triage, scoping, root cause investigation), Containment (isolation, blocking, account suspension), Eradication (malware removal, patch application, credential reset), Recovery (restore from backup, system rebuild, monitoring), Post-incident (lessons learned, documentation, improvement plan). Each phase includes specific tasks, owner assignments, and SLAs. The playbook includes communication templates for internal stakeholders (executives, legal, HR, PR) and external parties (customers, regulators, law enforcement) based on incident severity and data type. The incident response team (IRT) includes members from security, IT, legal, PR, HR, and executive leadership, with defined roles and escalation paths.</p>', 'DRAFT', 5, '2026-02-09 09:00:00'),
(96, 5, 11, 'Incident response with communication plan', '<h1>Security Incident Response - Communication Plan Added</h1><p>This revision adds a detailed communication plan to the incident response playbook. Communication principles: Timely (initial notification within 1 hour of Sev1 confirmation), Transparent (share what is known, avoid speculation), Accurate (facts only, reviewed by legal), and Empathetic (acknowledge impact, apologize when appropriate). Internal communication workflow: IRT notification (Slack channel #incident-response), Executive notification (text message for Sev1, email for Sev2, Jira ticket for Sev3/4), Employee communication (intranet post for Sev1 affecting >10% of employees, email for company-wide impact, team-specific for limited impact), and Board notification (within 24 hours for Sev1, quarterly for Sev2-4). External communication workflow: Customer notification (within 72 hours for data breach per GDPR, within 24 hours for service impact >2 hours per SLA), Regulatory notification (within 72 hours for GDPR breach, within 24 hours for SEC breach if material), Law enforcement (CISA, FBI for cybercrime, within 24 hours of confirmation), and Media (press release for public incidents, statement for media inquiries).</p><p>Communication templates are provided for each scenario, with variables for incident details (date, scope, impact, remediation, next steps). All external communications must be approved by legal and PR before release, with executive approval for customer and regulatory notifications. A communication log tracks all internal and external communications, including timestamp, audience, channel, message, and approval. Spokesperson assignments: CISO for technical details, CLO for legal and regulatory, CMO for customer and media, CEO for major incidents. The IRT conducts quarterly communication drills, testing templates and approval workflows. The communication plan has been reviewed by legal for compliance with breach notification laws (GDPR, CCPA, HIPAA, SEC) and by PR for messaging effectiveness.</p>', 'PENDING', 6, '2026-02-12 10:00:00'),
(97, 5, 12, 'Final security incident response', '<h1>Final Security Incident Response - Approved</h1><p>This approved playbook incorporates the communication plan from version 11 with final sign-off from the CISO, legal, and PR. The playbook becomes effective April 1, 2026, with all IRT members required to complete training and tabletop exercises before that date. Training includes: Playbook overview (2 hours, mandatory for all IRT members), Role-specific deep-dives (1 hour per role, technical for security, legal for compliance, PR for communication), and Quarterly tabletop exercises (4 hours each, simulating different incident scenarios: ransomware, data breach, DDoS, insider threat). The first tabletop exercise is scheduled for March 25th, with after-action report and playbook updates by March 30th.</p><p>Tools and access: IRT Slack channel with automated alerts from security tools (SIEM, EDR, CASB), Jira incident management project with templates for each severity level, PagerDuty for on-call rotations, and Sharepoint repository for playbook, templates, and runbooks. The playbook includes a post-incident review process: Root cause analysis within 5 business days, Corrective action plan within 10 business days, Lessons learned presentation to IRT and executive team within 15 business days, and Playbook update within 30 business days. Success metrics: Mean time to detect (MTTD) target 4 hours (baseline 48 hours), Mean time to respond (MTTR) target 2 hours (baseline 24 hours), Mean time to contain (MTTC) target 30 minutes (baseline 6 hours), and Mean time to recover (MTTR) target 4 hours (baseline 24 hours). The playbook will be reviewed annually, with updates as needed based on incident learnings, regulatory changes, and technology evolution. This playbook supersedes all previous incident response procedures.</p>', 'APPROVED', 7, '2026-02-15 16:00:00'),
(98, 3, 10, 'Performance review template', '<h1>Performance Review Template - Draft</h1><p>This document provides a standardized performance review template for annual and quarterly reviews, aligned with the employee handbook approved in version 9. The template includes sections: Employee information (name, role, manager, review period), Self-assessment (accomplishments, challenges, goals progress, development needs, open-ended reflection), Manager assessment (performance rating, goal achievement, competency evaluation, strengths, areas for improvement), Goal setting (next period goals - SMART criteria, action plan, success metrics), Development plan (training, mentorship, stretch assignments, promotion readiness), and Sign-off (employee signature, manager signature, HR acknowledgment). Performance ratings use a 5-point scale: 1 (Unsatisfactory), 2 (Below Expectations), 3 (Meets Expectations), 4 (Exceeds Expectations), 5 (Outstanding).</p><p>Competencies evaluated vary by role level: Individual contributors (7 competencies - technical skills, quality, productivity, collaboration, communication, problem-solving, adaptability), Managers (8 competencies - all IC competencies plus team development, performance management, strategic thinking), Directors (9 competencies - all manager competencies plus leadership, change management, financial acumen). Each competency includes behavioral anchors (specific examples of behaviors at each rating level) to improve consistency across managers. The template includes calibration guidance: Ratings follow a forced distribution for teams >10 employees (10% top performers - rating 5, 20% high performers - rating 4, 60% solid performers - rating 3, 10% below - ratings 1-2), with exceptions requiring HR approval. The review process includes self-assessment (employee completes first), manager assessment (manager completes after self-assessment), review meeting (discuss both assessments, agree on final ratings), and finalization (employee signs, manager submits to HR).</p>', 'DRAFT', 8, '2026-02-10 08:30:00'),
(99, 3, 11, 'Review template with self-assessment', '<h1>Performance Review Template - Self-Assessment Added</h1><p>This revision adds detailed guidance for the self-assessment section of the performance review template. The self-assessment prompts employees to reflect on: Achievements (list 3-5 key accomplishments from review period, including metrics and impact), Challenges (describe 2-3 challenges faced, how they were addressed, what was learned), Goals progress (rate progress on each goal from previous review: Not Started, In Progress, Completed, Exceeded, with comments), Development needs (identify 2-3 skills or competencies to develop, why important, planned actions), and Career aspirations (short-term 12-18 months, long-term 3-5 years, interest in leadership, mobility preferences). The self-assessment is limited to 1500 characters per section to encourage conciseness, with optional attachment for additional detail.</p><p>Manager assessment guidance adds: Calibration examples for each competency (e.g., for Collaboration: Rating 5 - \"Actively seeks diverse perspectives, resolves conflicts constructively, recognized by peers as team player\"; Rating 1 - \"Works in silo, resists feedback, causes team friction\"). Managers must provide specific examples for any rating of 1-2 or 4-5, with generic comments (\"good job,\" \"needs improvement\") prohibited. The template includes a section for 360-degree feedback (optional for individual contributors, required for managers and above), collecting input from peers, direct reports, and other stakeholders. Feedback is anonymous (collected by HR, summarized themes shared with manager). The self-assessment and 360 feedback are visible to the employee before the review meeting, enabling informed discussion. The template has been piloted with 20 managers and 50 employees, with feedback incorporated: shorter sections (reduced from 2000 to 1500 characters), clearer rating definitions, and automated reminders for completion.</p>', 'PENDING', 9, '2026-02-13 11:30:00'),
(100, 3, 12, 'Final annual performance review form', '<h1>Final Annual Performance Review Form - Approved</h1><p>This approved performance review template incorporates self-assessment guidance from version 11 with final approval from HR leadership and legal. The form is implemented in the HRIS (Workday) effective March 1, 2026, for the annual review cycle covering January-December 2026 (reviews completed in January 2027). Quarterly reviews for new hires (first 12 months) and underperformers (Performance Improvement Plans) will use an abbreviated version of the form (fewer competencies, no 360 feedback). The form includes accessibility features (screen reader compatible, high contrast mode, keyboard navigation) compliant with WCAG 2.1 AA standards.</p><p>Implementation timeline: Manager training on the new form and calibration process (February 15-28, 6 sessions, 2 hours each), Employee training on self-assessment (e-learning module, 20 minutes, available March 1st), Pilot for Q1 2026 reviews (April 1-30 with 50 managers and 200 employees), Full rollout for mid-year reviews (July 1-31) and annual reviews (January 1-31, 2027). Success metrics: Manager satisfaction (target 4.0/5), Employee satisfaction (target 4.0/5), Completion timeliness (target 95% within 30 days of review period end), Rating distribution (target within 5% of forced distribution guidelines), and Promotion correlation (target rating 4-5 employees 2x more likely to be promoted vs rating 3). The form will be reviewed after the pilot (May 2026) and after annual cycle (February 2027) for continuous improvement. Legal has approved the form for compliance with employment laws (no discriminatory language, consistent application, documentation standards). This form supersedes all previous performance review templates and becomes the official form for all regular employees effective immediately.</p>', 'APPROVED', 10, '2026-02-16 14:00:00')
